Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the test materials.
Text: The initial total thickness of the multilayer steel was about 30 mm with individual layer of about 0.5 mm. Firstly, TWIP and C300 maraging steels were initially cut into thin sheets with the diameter of 60 mm and the thickness of 0.5 mm. Secondly, the surface rusts of steels were polished by abrasive papers, and then staked, welded and vacuum pumped to keep the multilayer steels inside the blank with a vacuum degree of 10-2 Pa, the schematic diagram is shown in Fig. 2 a)-2c). Thirdly, the billet was heated at 1200oC with holding time of 40min and then hot rolled to a final thickness of 6 mm with a total reduction of 80%.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the test materials.
Text: Firstly, TWIP and C300 maraging steels were initially cut into thin sheets with the diameter of 60 mm and the thickness of 0.5 mm. Secondly, the surface rusts of steels were polished by abrasive papers, and then staked, welded and vacuum pumped to keep the multilayer steels inside the blank with a vacuum degree of 10-2 Pa, the schematic diagram is shown in Fig. 2 a)-2c). Thirdly, the billet was heated at 1200°C with holding time of 40min and then hot rolled to a final thickness of 6 mm with a total reduction of 80%. The hot rolled multilayer TWIP/maraging steel was marked as HR steel, and the HR steel was aged at 485oC for 4 h, followed by air cooling, labeled as HR-A steel. In order to improve interface bonding strength and tensile strength, the HR steels were cold rolled to a thickness of 3 mm with a total reduction of 62.5%, respectively, compared with HR steels, denoted as HR-CR3 steel.

Table_topic: Microstructure and mechanical properties of the experimental steels with different cooling parameters.
Text: Pre-fast cooling rate (°C/s) 115 Pre-fast cooling temperature (°C) 710 Post-fast cooling rate (°C/s) 93 Post-cooling temperature (°C) 550. The continuously cast plates were reheated to 1200°C for 2h in a box type resistance furnace, hot rolled to 11mm thickness using a two-high 450mm hot rolling mill and air-cooled to room temperature. Cylindrical specimens of diameter 6mm and 15mm long were machined from the hot rolled plate to conduct TMCP experiments in a Gleeble 3800 thermo-mechanical simulator. The specimens were reheated to 1200°C for 180s to ensure complete austenitization and cooled to 850°C at a cooling rate of 10°C/s. After holding for 20s to eliminate the temperature gradient, the specimens were subjected to 50% compressive strain at a strain rate of 3s-1, followed by cooling to room temperature at cooling rates of 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20 and 40°C/s, respectively. The plates of 60 mm thickness were reheated to 1200 °C for 2 h and hot rolled to 5 mm thickness using the two-high Ф450 mm experimental hot rolling mill equipped with ultrafast cooling (UFC) system developed in our laboratory. The hot rolling process was accomplished with reduction ratio of ~68% in the recrystallization region and ~75% in the non-recrystallization region. The finish rolling temperature was 840 °C. After hot rolling, the strips were subjected to pre-fast cooling stage, air cooling stage, and post-fast cooling stage on the run-out table, and then placed in the coil box to simulate the industrial coiling process.

Table_topic: Tensile data extracted from stress-strain curves of coarse and fine grained ferritic stainless steel.
Text: This material was received in the hot rolled condition and the initial microstructure consisted of equiaxed ferrite grains with mean size of 120 μm. By the proposed thermo-mechanical treatment, the microstructure was refined to an average grain size of 5 μm. Fig. 1 shows the schematic of the thermo-mechanical processing route conducted to produce fine-grained ferritic stainless steel from initial coarse-grained sample. Step 1 was the solution annealing at the temperature of 1200 °C for 7200s conducted to produce initial coarse grained microstructure with uniform chemical composition. Step 2 was the cold rolling of sample to about 90% thickness reduction to produce heavily cold worked material. Step 3 was the recrystallization annealing at 800 °C for 180 s. Also, sample was quenched immediately in water after recrystallization annealing to prevent grain growth just after recrystallization.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the as-built and heat-treated specimens.
Text: The studied hybrid additively manufactured material uses a commercial Uddeholm AISI 421 stainless steel as the substrate, and Corrax, a maraging stainless steel, printed on top. An EOS M290 system was used to build the ɸ12 × 120 mm Corrax steel cylinders on top of 420 under an Argon atmosphere using the laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) technique. The laser power, scanning speed, hatching distance and layer thickness were 258.7 W, 1066.7 mm/s, 100 µm, and 30 µm, respectively. The laser beam was rotated 67° between successive layers during the process. The platform temperature was kept at 80 °C during the printing process to reduce the residual stresses at the interface. The commercial heat treatment of 420 steel includes austenitization at 1010–1030 °C followed by tempering at 230–300 °C, while the heat treatment of Corrax includes austenitization at approximately 900 °C followed by aging at 500–550 °C. In this work, we examined combinations of austenitization and aging temperatures and concluded that a hybrid heat treatment cycle in an Argon atmosphere optimizes mechanical properties and compatibility between 420 and Corrax steels. We chose the 420 austenitization temperature and the Corrax aging temperature as described in the following. The hybrid steel was heated at 15 °C/min to the maximum temperature of 1010 °C and then held for 30 min, followed by quenching with high-pressure Argon, to obtain a fully martensitic matrix. Table_topic: Table IV Average Tensile Properties of Investigated Alloys
Text: Table I shows the chemical compositions of the investigated alloys. Vacuum-induction-melted ingots with dimensions of 300 × 150 × 50 mm were reheated to 1200 °C for 2 hours and hot rolled with a finishing temperature above 800 °C, followed by air cooling to room temperature. The thickness of the hot-rolled sheets was 4.5 mm. They were pickled in a 10 pct HCl solution and then cold rolled to a thickness of 1 mm. The cold-rolled sheets were annealed using an infrared heating furnace, with heating and cooling rates of 10 °C/s. The intercritical annealing temperatures of 660 °C for the L-Al alloy, taking into account the calculated equilibrium austenite fraction. The holding time at each annealing temperature was 2 minutes. Specimens were prepared by mechanical polishing followed by chemical polishing in a 10 pct HF+H2O2 solution.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of experimental steels.
Text: The chemical composition was designed based on our previous study . The steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace and forged into ingots with a thickness of 80 mm. The ingot was homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h in a muffle furnace, and then hot rolled to 12 mm plate via six passes with minimum reduction of 20% per pass, followed by quenching to room temperature. The depth of decarburized layer was estimated to be ~0.2 mm during homogenization according to the method proposed in an early study , which was descaled during hot-rolling. The Ac1 and Ac3 temperatures of experimental steel were determined to be 680 °C and 874 °C, respectively, by using thermal dilatometer (DIL805A) as shown in Fig. 1 . In type I, samples were intercritically annealed at 690 °C for 30 min, and then air cooled to room temperature, which were referred henceforth as IA30.  Tensile tests were carried out at room temperature at a strain rate of 0.001 s-1 by using a universal testing machine (WDW-200D), and specimens for tensile test were cut along the rolling direction with dimensions of 25 mm gage and 5 mm in diameter, according to the ASTM-E8 standard.

Table_topic: Table 2 Tensile properties of three pipeline steels
Text: All steels were melted in a 210t converter furnace and refined in a ladle furnace to reduce the harmful compounds. The steel was cast into slabs of 300 mm × 1400 mm × 2400 mm size by continuous casting. The slabs were soaked at 1200 °C for 2-3 h and then rolled to different thick plates through TMCP, which were rough-rolled with the range of 1050-1150 °C, and subsequently, the plates were rolled to the thicknesses of 18.4 mm for X80, 17.8 mm for X90, and 14.8 mm for X100 in a finishing mill at 790-820 °C, followed by accelerated cooling at a rate of 25-30 °C/s. Samples used for evaluation of mechanical properties and microstructural observation were cut from these steel plates. Standard tensile specimens with the dimension of 12.5 mm × 135 mm and a gage with a length of 50 mm along the rolling direction were also used. Specimens for fine microstructure observation were first cut into 300-μm-thick foils and grinded on SiC abrasive papers to achieve a thickness of 60 μm.

The steel was cast into slabs of 300 mm × 1400 mm × 2400 mm size by continuous casting. The slabs were soaked at 1200 °C for 2-3 h and then rolled to different thick plates through TMCP, which were rough-rolled with the range of 1050-1150 °C, and subsequently, the plates were rolled to the thicknesses of 18.4 mm for X80, 17.8 mm for X90, and 14.8 mm for X100 in a finishing mill at 790-820 °C, followed by accelerated cooling at a rate of 25-30 °C/s. Samples used for evaluation of mechanical properties and microstructural observation were cut from these steel plates. Standard tensile specimens with the dimension of 12.5 mm × 135 mm and a gage with a length of 50 mm along the rolling direction were also used. Specimens for fine microstructure observation were first cut into 300-μm-thick foils and grinded on SiC abrasive papers to achieve a thickness of 60 μm.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of experimental steels.
Text: Based on the design strategy of microstructure, the nominal chemical composition of the experimental steel was Fe-0.117C-2.88Mn-1.13Ni-0.89Cu-0.4Si-0.2Mo-0.07Nb (in wt.%). The experimental steel was melted in vacuum and cast into ingots of ~80 mm thickness, which were then homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h. The homogenized ingots were rolled to ~6 mm thick strips using several passes with a minimum reduction of ~25 % per pass. The hot rolling started at 1050 °C and finished at 880 °C followed by cooling in air. Partitioning and tempering was carried out in box furnace after hot rolling. The partitioning was performed at 700 °C for 1 h, followed by cooling in water, and is referred as steel P700. The tempering was performed at 660oCfor 0.5 h, and labeled as steel P/T700-660.

Text: The gas-atomized SS-CX powder was produced by Vlory with particle sizes in the range of 15–53 µm. The 304 stainless steel substrate with size of 280 mm × 280 mm × 25 mm was used for testing. Before each test, the substrate was preheated to 60 °C. The SLM experiments were carried out using the HBD-280 device (Guangdong Hanbang 3D Tech Co., Ltd., China) equipped with an IPG fiber laser, as shown in Fig. 2(a). The laser wavelength was 1070 nm, and the spot size was 50 µm. In the SLM process, high-purity argon gas was used as the protective gas to form an airtight chamber to ensure that the oxygen content was less than 500 ppm. To determine the heat treatment scheme, different solution parameters and aging parameters were employed in the SS-CX samples treated with SLM, fabricated under the optimal process parameters. The solution parameters and aging parameters were listed in Table 3. All the heat treatment tests were conducted in a Normanbell NB380A vacuum annealing furnace. The heating rate was 10 ºC/min. Table_topic: Room temperature tensile properties of specimens after different treatments.
Text: The studied steel was melted using vacuum induction technique. The ingot was heated to 1000 °C and held for 3.6 ks, and then forged at 800-1000 °C to produce 21 mm thick plate. The chemical composition of the studied high-Mn steel is shown in The thickness of Fe-30Mn-0.11C steel was reduced to 90% by cold rolling. Then, recrystallization was carried out over the temperature range from 500 to 1000 °C for 3.6 ks to obtain various grain sizes. Subsequently, the samples were water-quenched. In addition, the as-forged specimens were solution-treated at 1000 °C for 3.6 ks to produce coarse grained microstructures. Tensile specimens with a gauge length of 10 mm, width of 2 mm and thickness of 2 mm were prepared from the cold rolled and annealed and solution treated plates, respectively.

Table_topic: Measured mechanical properties of QAT and Q&P samples.
Text: The ingots were homogenized at 1250 °C for 2 h, then hot rolled to a final thickness of 4 mm through 7 passes. And subsequently, the steel was cooled in a furnace to room temperature obtaining the microstructure of ferrite and pearlite. The hot-rolled sheets were then cold rolled to 1.2 mm with a reduction ratio of 70% after pickling in 10% hydrochloric acid. Then the cold rolled sheets were subjected to the different annealing processes using a tube furnace and salt baths. The experimental samples were divided into two groups, as shown in Fig. 1 . The first group (QAT = quenching and austempering) was partially austenitized at 840 °C for 240s, rapidly quenched to 460 °C for the duration of different times (4s) and finally quenched to room temperature.

Table_topic: Measured mechanical properties of QAT and Q&P samples.
Text: The ingots were homogenized at 1250 °C for 2 h, then hot rolled to a final thickness of 4 mm through 7 passes. And subsequently, the steel was cooled in a furnace to room temperature obtaining the microstructure of ferrite and pearlite. The hot-rolled sheets were then cold rolled to 1.2 mm with a reduction ratio of 70% after pickling in 10% hydrochloric acid. Then the cold rolled sheets were subjected to the different annealing processes using a tube furnace and salt baths. The experimental samples were divided into two groups, as shown in Fig. 1 . The second group (Q&P = quenching and partitioning) was treated in the same way as the first group but with a quenching step involving supercooling from 840 °C to 175 °C (temperature between Ms and Mf) before reheating to 460 °C for different times, and the quenching process aimed to obtain a reasonable amount of martensite before partitioning and further enrich austenite with carbon during subsequent partitioning. These samples were isothermal at 460 °C for the corresponding times (4s).

Table_topic: Table II Mechanical Properties of the Newly Designed Duplex Material Compared with Some Advanced High-Strength Steels
Text: The alloy was prepared using an induction furnace under nitrogen atmosphere, followed by the pressure electroslag remelting process. The remelted ingots with dimensions of 50 mm × 70 mm × 700 mm were homogenized at 1373 K (1100 °C) for 120 minutes, hot rolled at temperatures between 1373 K and 1473 K (1100 °C and 1200 °C) to a final thickness of 20 mm, and finally solution annealed at 1373 K (1100 °C) for 30 minutes. The solutionized material was cut perpendicular to the hot-rolling direction and machined to workpieces in the form of plates of 5 mm thickness. The workpieces were cold rolled from 5 to 1 mm thickness (~80 pct area reduction) and annealed at 1373 K (1100 °C) for 180 seconds; the workpieces were finally quenched in water. Based on Thermo-Calc computation results, the austenite phase in the newly designed DSS under the aforementioned annealing condition consists of 0.43 wt pct nitrogen.

Schematic diagram of annealing process and specimen direction for high-Mn austenitic steels in this study is presented in Fig. 1 and specimen information on cold-rolling, annealing and direction condition used in this study was shown in Table 2.The microstructure of transverse–longitudinal (T–L) direction specimen specimen was observed by optical microscopy.

Table_topic: Engineering tensile test data at 25 and -196 degC for the HEA/high-Mn MLS and nonclad HEA and high-Mn steel sheets.
Text: The HEA ingot (8 kg) was rolled at 1100-900 °C to a 12-mm-thick plate after homogenization at 1100 °C for 6 h. The actual composition of the HEA, measured by inductively coupled plasma mass spectroscopy, was determined to be V8 . 95Cr9 . 34Fe43 . 00Co30 . 20Ni5.21 (at.%). The austenitic high-Mn TWIP steel was also fabricated using a vacuum induction furnace with a composition of 0.45C-24Mn-6Cr (wt.%) with small amounts of P, S, and N. After homogenization at 1200 °C for 1 h, the high-Mn steel ingot was rolled at 1100-900 °C, water-cooled to 450 °C, held at this temperature for 1 h, and cooled to room temperature to produce a 12-mm-thick plate. The welded stack (total thickness: 36 mm) was homogenized at 1200 °C for 1 h, hot-rolled at 1100-900 °C, and then cold-rolled to produce a 2-mm-thick sheet. This MLS was annealed at 850 °C for 10 min under an argon atmosphere and water-quenched to obtain fully recrystallized microstructures in both HEA and high-Mn layers. The fabrication procedures for the high-Mn/HEA/high-Mn MLS are illustrated in Fig. 1 .

Table_topic: Table 2 Tensile properties of the steels after final annealing
Text: Figure 1 presents the applied TMTs on the steels. The as-cast strip of the TRC steel was cut into small pieces (2.4 × 40 × 100 mm) and homogenized at 1200 °C for 30 min in vacuum. To have similar amount of reduction ratios to those applied in warm and cold rolling stages of the TRC steel (50% and 33%, respectively), the 3 mm sheets were warm rolled at 650 °C to 1.5 mm and subsequently cold rolled to 1 mm in thickness. The cold rolled sheets of both IC and TRC steels were finally annealed at 800 °C for 1 h under protective Ar atmosphere. All specimens were air cooled after hot/warm rolling or annealing.

Table_topic: Table 2 Tensile properties of the steels after final annealing
Text: Figure 1 presents the applied TMTs on the steels. The homogenized strip was warm rolled at 650 °C to a thickness of 1.2 mm and then cold rolled to a final thickness of 0.8 mm . In the case of the IC steel, the ingot was homogenized at 1200 °C for 1 h, followed by hot rolling between 1100 and 1000 °C to produce plates with a thickness of 20 mm. The hot rolled plate was warm rolled at 650 °C to 3 mm in thickness and then subjected to an intermediate annealing at 850 °C for 15 min. To have similar amount of reduction ratios to those applied in warm and cold rolling stages of the TRC steel (50% and 33%, respectively), the 3 mm sheets were warm rolled at 650 °C to 1.5 mm and subsequently cold rolled to 1 mm in thickness. The cold rolled sheets of both IC and TRC steels were finally annealed at 800 °C for 1 h under protective Ar atmosphere. All specimens were air cooled after hot/warm rolling or annealing.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the B-pillars made of medium-Mn steel and Boron steel.
Text: The medium-Mn steel used in this study was developed by the Central Iron and Research Institute of China. Their chemical composition (wt.%) is shown in Table 1 . The basic process of producing the medium-Mn steel is to quench the prototype steel to obtain a martensite microstructure first and then anneal the quenched steel in the bipolar region (Ac1-Ac3) for austenite reversion transformation to obtain a multi-phase microstructure that consists of austenite, ultrafine ferrite and precipitated phase. The annealing time varies from 2 to 6h depending the content of C and Mn, and the desired mechanical properties such as yield strength, tensile strength and elongation. For the microstructure examination in TEM and EBSD, samples were firstly ground mechanically to a thickness of about 0.04mm, and then electro-polished in a twin-jet machine in a solution of 5% perchloric acid and 95% alcohol at about -20°C.

Table_topic: Table 3 Tensile and hardness results for low and medium carbon steels
Text: The carbon steel samples with 100 × 40 × 30 mm dimensions were cut and prepared from the as-cast plates using CNC machine for hot rolling process. The samples were hot-rolled at 1200 °C for 30 min followed by air cooling as shown in Fig. 1. The hot-rolled samples were then passed over a series of 6 passes down to a final thickness of 15 mm. After each pass, the sample was then heated to 1200 °C for 10 min in air before being rolled again. Two different heat treatment processes (QAMf and Q&P) were applied in this study, Fig. 2. The first heat treatment of low carbon steel (0.16C) was heating up to intercritical annealing zone (830 °C) followed by quenching in a salt bath after martensitic finish (160 °C). The second one was heating above Ac3 (830 °C) followed by quenching in salt bath after martensitic start (160 °C). The treated samples at 830 °C were in intercritical annealing zone of the two-phase area (i.e. ferrite and austenite). The treated samples at 830 °C were above AC3. The microstructure of trade Q&P steels basically consists of martensite (70%-80%) formed during quenching, ferrite (10%-20%) formed from the austenite phase during slow cooling, and dispersed retained austenite (5%-10%) stabilized by carbon enrichment during partitioning. The investigated low and medium hot rolled carbon steels were heat-treated using QAMf and Q&P processes.

Table_topic: The statistic mechanical properties of the two medium steels before and after tensile deformation, i.e. yield strength, tensile strength and uniform elongation.
Text: After homogenization at 1473 K for 60min, hot rolling was conducted in eight passes between 750 and 1050 °C and then air quenching to room temperature. The hot-rolled plates were cold rolled for a total reduction of ~75% in multiple passes. The complex microstructure consisting of ferrite, retained austenite and co-precipitates was obtained by a two-step procedure of partitioning and tempering. Table 1 shows the nominal compositions and heat treatment windows of the two medium-Mn steels. Uniaxial tensile tests were conducted at room temperature (RT) along the rolling direction with a gauge length and width of 25 and 6 mm, respectively, using a constant strain rate of 4 × 10-4 s-1. The tensile properties of the two medium Mn steels before hydrogen charging are shown.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of Fe-18Mn-9Cr-2Al-xC steels tested at RT, 300 degC and 600 degC.
Text: The model alloys used in the present work were Fe-18Mn-9Cr-2Al-xC steels (x = 0, 0.1, 0.3, and 0.5 in wt. % nominally) and the analyzed chemical composition of the alloys are summarized in Table 1 . 60 kg-scale rectangular-shaped ingots with a thickness of 80 mm were prepared by induction melting in an argon atmosphere. The cast ingots were subjected to homogenization heat treatment at 1150 °C for 2 h to eliminate segregation of alloying elements such as Mn and Al, and then were hot-rolled to 20 mm-thick plates with a reduction in thickness of 75%. The finishing temperature of hot-rolling was around 950 °C. The hot-rolled plated were heat-treated at 800 °C for 2 h and then quenched in water (as heat-treated condition). Flat tensile specimens (2 mm in thickness, 4 mm in width, and 12 mm in gauge length) were cut from the plate such that the uniaxial loading direction is parallel to the rolling direction (RD) of the plate.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of G91 steel plate in as-received condition.
Text: G91 steel plates (500 mm × 250 mm × 30 mm) in the normalized (1050 °C for 1 h with air cooling) and tempered (750 °C for 1 h and air cooling) conditions was used in the present investigation. The chemical composition of this material is given in Table 1. Small blocks of size 50 × 20 × 22 mm were cut longitudinally from the as-received plate in order to study the effect of heat treatment and hot rolling on the mechanical and microstructural properties. These blocks were subjected to solutionizing treatment at 1150 °C for 1 h in order to eliminate the effect of prior history on microstructure. The mechanical properties of as-received (AR) G91 steel corresponding to test temperatures (RT and 650 °C) are listed in Table 2.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical properties of A700–A760 steels
Text: The Al content in majority of Mn-Al medium-Mn steels was greater than 2 wt%. The chemical composition of the experimental steel is listed in Table 1. A 90-kg ingot of the experimental steel was prepared by vacuum induction melting. The ingot was forged into a billet with a section dimension of 70 mm × 60 mm. The billet was homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h and then hot-rolled to 4-mm-thick sheet involving nine passes. The finish rolling temperature was ~ 900 °C. After finish rolling, the sheet was finally cooled to room temperature in air. Subsequently, the as-hot-rolled sheet was subjected to intercritical annealing, which involved intercritical annealing at 700 °C for 60 min, respectively, followed by air cooling to room temperature.

Table_topic: Average tensile and impact properties of the two steels isothermally treated at 320degC.
Text: The chemical compositions of the two steels, the Al-free steel and the Al-containing steel (hereafter the 1.19Al steel), are given in Table 1. The ingots melted by vacuum induction furnace were hot-forged into square bars at a finishing temperature of around 920°C. Specimens were all austenitized at 920°C for 30min, isothermally treated in a salt bath at a temperature of 320°C for different holding times from 84 to 420min, and finally air cooled to room temperature. Disks of 3mm in diameter were twin-jet electropolished to perforation at room temperature. For the same steel, similar microstructures were observed when isothermally treated at 320°C for different holding times. Fig. 1(a) and (c) shows typical optical metallographs of the Al-free and the 1.19Al steels isothermally treated at 320°C for a holding time of 420min.

Table_topic: Average tensile and impact properties of the two steels isothermally treated at 320degC.
Text: The chemical compositions of the two steels, the Al-free steel and the Al-containing steel (hereafter the 1.19Al steel), are given in Table 1. The ingots melted by vacuum induction furnace were hot-forged into square bars at a finishing temperature of around 920°C. Specimens were all austenitized at 920°C for 30min, isothermally treated in a salt bath at a temperature of 320°C for different holding times from 84 to 420min, and finally air cooled to room temperature. Disks of 3mm in diameter were twin-jet electropolished to perforation at room temperature. For the same steel, similar microstructures were observed when isothermally treated at 320°C for different holding times. Fig. 1(a) and (c) shows typical optical metallographs of the Al-free and the 1.19Al steels isothermally treated at 320°C for a holding time of 420min.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the material in different processing conditions. RC, CR, and RX denote recovery-annealed, cold-rolled and fully recrystallized condition, respectively.
Text: The melt was cast into 100 kg ingots, followed by homogenization annealing of the slabs at 1150 °C for 5 h in a muffle furnace. Then, the 140 mm thick ingots were forged at 1150 °C to a reduced thickness of 55 mm and again homogenized. Afterward, the slabs were hot rolled at 1150 °C to a final height of 10 mm. Rods with a diameter of 10 mm and a length of 35 mm were cut out of the hot-rolled slabs perpendicular to the rolling direction for further deformation by ECAP. ECAP passes of 1 were realized with air cooling after each pass and a sample rotation of 90° between consecutive passes to follow route BC . Additional heat treatment was performed in a sandbath furnace at 600 °C. Specimens with the dimensions 8 mm × 10 mm × 1 mm (extrusion direction (ED) × normal direction (ND) × transverse direction (TD), respectively) were cut from the deformed rods.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of nickel-free austenitic stainless steels
Text: Six experimental interstitially-alloyed Cr-Mn austenitic stainless steels with chemical compositions given in Table 1 were ingot-cast in a laboratory vacuum induction furnace under a protective nitrogen gas atmosphere. The ingots, weighing 100kg, were sectioned into 25mm thick sections, annealed at 1250°C for 30min, followed by hot rolling to a final thickness of 12mm with a finishing temperature above 950°C. The hot-rolled sheets were annealed at 1050°C for 15min and quenched in water prior to the machining of Charpy-V impact specimens.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical properties of the experimental steels
Text: According to the scheme presented in Fig. 1, the plates were reheated to 1200 °C to homogenize the structure before rolling. The rough-rolling temperature started at 1150 °C above the nonrecrystallization temperature of austenite for both steels. The finish rolling stage was started at 920 °C and finished rolling at 820 and 815 °C for steel A and B, respectively. The rolled plates steel A and B were air-cooled to the start cooling temperature of about 780 °C were water-cooled to 550 and 450 °C and then were air-cooled to room temperature. The final plates with thickness of 21.4 and 22.3 mm for steel A and B, respectively, were obtained. Ten tensile specimens, 160 mm in total length and 20 mm in effective width, 50 mm in gage length, were machined from the plates with the longitudinal axis parallel to the longitudinal direction, and tensile tests were carried out on an INSTRON 4206 machine at a strain rate of 5 mm/min at room temperature.

Table_topic: Table 4 Tensile properties before and after 1% pre-strain and thermal aging treatment at the temperature of 200 °C and 250 °C of the API X60, X70, and X80 pipeline steels
Text: After reheating treatment at temperatures above 1100 °C, the X60 steel was rolled in austenite recrystallization region, while the X70 and X80 steels were rolled in austenite non-recrystallization region where fine elongated austenite grains can be obtained by rolling with a high rolling reduction ratio above 70%. The hot-rolled steel plates were rapidly cooled from start cooling temperatures above Ar3 to finish cooling temperatures between 500 and 600 °C at various cooling rates. Steel specimens obtained from the 1/2 thickness location of the rolled steel plates were mechanically polished and etched by a 3% Nital solution. Sub-size round tensile specimens with a gage diameter of 6.3 mm and a gage length of 25.4 mm were obtained from the 1/2 thickness of rolled plates in the longitudinal direction.

Table_topic: Table 4 Tensile properties before and after 1% pre-strain and thermal aging treatment at the temperature of 200 °C and 250 °C of the API X60, X70, and X80 pipeline steels

Text: The 100 kg steel ingot was prepared using a high-frequency vacuum induction furnace. The ingot was then forged into billets of dimensions ~100 mm × 100 mm. Schematic diagram of rolling and heat treatment process of the experimental steel is shown in Fig. 1 . The billets were hot-rolled to 12 mm steel plates via seven passes, after homogenization at 1200 °C for 2 h. The finish rolling temperature was greater than 1030 °C. Subsequently, the plates were directly quenched to room temperature (RT) and designated as sample DQ (directly quenched).

Table_topic: Mean yield strength (YS), ultimate tensile strength (UTS), total elongation, uniform elongation and 28 J transition temperatures including 95% confidence intervals. Yield strength (YS) refers to the stress for 0.2% plastic strain.
Text: Experimental slabs were hot rolled and directly quenched using a laboratory hot rolling mill. Based on the austenite grain growth studies described below, 55 mm thick slabs were reheated at 1225 °C for 2 h. This was followed by hot rolling with 6 passes to a final plate thickness of 6 mm as detailed in Table 2 . The estimated recrystallization stop temperatures were in the range of 880-890 °C and therefore the 5th and 6th rolling passes were performed below that temperature with the aim of obtaining pancaked austenite prior to direct quenching. Immediately after the final rolling pass at 800 °C the plate was directly quenched in a water bath at room temperature. The cooling rate during direct quenching measured with a thermocouple embedded in the middle of the slab prior to rolling was nearly 100 °C/s until approximately 400-450 °C from where the cooling rate started to slow down to 50 °C/s before reaching room temperature.

Table_topic: Table III Tensile Properties of Alloys
Text: The alloy was manufactured as a 34 kg ingot of 100 × 170 × 230 mm dimensions using a vacuum furnace with the composition: The ingot was reheated to 1473 K (1200 °C) for rough rolling to make 25 to 30 mm slabs followed by air cooling. The slabs were then reheated to 1473 K (1200 °C) and hot-rolled with the temperature maintained above 1173 K (900 °C) down to 3 mm thickness. Microstructural evolution was fulfilled on dilatometric samples of dimensions 2 × 3 × 10 mm machined from hot-rolled sheets, using a push-rod BAHR DIL805 high-speed dilatometer with radio frequency induction heating; the equipment has been described elsewhere. According to the dilatometric curves for bainitic transformation (Figure 4), after intercritical annealing at 1073 K (800 °C) for 5 minutes, alloys isothermally held at 603 K (330 °C) for 30 minutes.

Table_topic: Tensile properties results of Q&P samples with different quenching temperatures. (Note: tensile property results of Q&P-175 is from Q&P-30 in Ref. [20].)
Text: The ingots were homogenized at 1250 °C for 2h and then hot rolled to a final thickness of 4 mm through 7 passes. Subsequently, the steels were cooled in a furnace to room temperature and obtained ferrite and pearlite. Then cold rolled to 1.2 mm with a reduction ratio of 70% after pickling in 10% hydrochloric acid. Then the cold rolled sheets were subjected to the different annealing processes using a tube furnace and salt baths. Here, the annealing temperature is selected as 840 °C and the volume fraction of ferrite is about 32.6% according our previous study . In order to cooperate with CGL, high-temperature short-time overaging treatment (i.e., 460°C-30s) were conducted, as shown in Fig. 1b. The specimens were heated to partial austenitizing temperature 840 °C and held for 240s. Afterwards, the steels were rapidly placed in the salt bath furnace with different quenching temperatures (150 °C) for 30s and subsequently overaged at 460 °C for 30s followed by water quenching.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the specimens measured at different stages during the thermomechanical treatment

Table_topic: Table II Mechanical Properties of the Experimental Steels After Q&P Treatment
Text: The experimental steels were smelted in a vacuum induction furnace and cast as 150 kg ingots. Slabs with thicknesses of 30 mm were heated to 1200 °C by a heating furnace for homogenization. The slabs were held at 1200 °C for 2 hours before air cooling to 1050 °C for hot rolling. The homogenized slabs were rolled to 3 mm on a trial hot rolling mill with a roll diameter of 450 mm via 7 passes and a total thickness reduction of 90 pct. The finishing temperature of hot rolling was controlled at 900 °C. Based on thermodynamic calculation results from Thermo-Calc, three different cooling modes after hot rolling were designed to ensure different initial microstructures: (i) Quenching (HR-QC), the hot-rolled plate was quenched to room temperature with water;The samples were put into a 900 °C muffle furnace for 300 seconds (average heating rate of ~ 5 °C/s) before the Q&P process, and the actual austenitizing time was approximately 120 seconds. The fully austenitized steels were cooled to the QT by a salt bath at a cooling rate of 71 °C/s to inhibit ferrite formation. The quenching temperature of 230 °C was determined with the constrained carbon equilibrium (CCE) model using the nominal composition of the steel.  Therefore, immediately after the initial quenching to QT, the samples were put into the second salt bath furnace, heated to 400 °C at a rate of 4 °C/s and then kept at 400 °C for 50 seconds. Finally, the steels were quenched in water.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of QP980 samples with different initial heating rates.
Text: Rectangular sheet samples with dimensions of approximate 4.3 mm (width) ×10.5 mm (length) ×1.20 mm (thickness) were wire-cut along the rolling direction and then mechanically polished for quenching and partitioning (Q&P) treatment. Q&P treatment simulated using a DIL 805 L quenching dilatometer. The rectangular samples was firstly induction heated to 1210 K (just above the austenite finish temperature Ac 3) with preset heating rates of 4 K/s, respectively, followed by quenching into 583 K (below the martensite start temperature M s) at 70 K/s, and then were reheated to 703 K and partitioned for 90 s, finished by cooling at 30 K/s to room temperature. Samples directly quenched from 1210 K were prepared for comparison. The austenitization completes at 1157 K (the austenite finish temperature Ac 3). Regarding to the conventional slow-heating annealing, the cold-rolled ferrite/pearlite microstructure undergoes full recovery and recrystallization prior to austenitization. However, all samples in the present study were fully austenitized since the peak temperature of 1210 K is about 50 K higher than the Ac 3 temperature. The initial heating temperature was set to be 1173 K (just above the Ac3 temperature) and quenching/partitioning parameters were the same as shown in Fig. 1.

Text: The materials to be tested is the type 304 stainless steels in accordance with the material requirements of the ASME B&PV Code Section II, which are broadly used for safety class components such as piping, reactor vessel internals, and containments for radioactive material transportation in nuclear power plants. The tensile test specimens illustrated in Fig. 1 were machined in the shape of round bars with a uniform length of 32 mm, a gauge length of 25 mm, and a diameter of 6 mm for quasi-static testing and 5 mm for dynamic testing, respectively, in accordance with the testing requirements of the ASTM E8 standard.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the 304Cu steel after various reversion annealing treatments compared to those of as-received (hot rolled) and cold-rolled conditions.
Text: The steel was made as a laboratory casting using standard melting practice. For cold rolling, the steel was received in the form of a hot rolled sheet, ~3.2 mm in thickness. The as-received steel sheet was cold rolled in a laboratory rolling mill to 0.93 mm thickness (~71% reduction) and subsequently annealed in a Gleeble 3800 simulator at various temperatures in the range 650-950 °C using isothermal holding times between 1 and 5400 s. For reversion treatment, the samples were heated at 200 °C/s to the annealing temperature, held for desired duration and then cooled at the same rate at least down to 300 °C. The initial grain size of the sample was estimated as 31 ± 4 μm. Cold rolling in 13 passes (about 15% each) to the total reduction of 71% resulted in the DIM fraction of 80%, so that still a significant amount of deformed austenite (DA) was retained. The objective of the applied reversion treatment applied was to improve the strength properties of the steel.

Table_topic: Average tensile test values of specimens.
Text: The steel was first melted in a vacuum furnace and cast into a 100 kg ingot. The ingot was forged into billets with thickness of 60 mm. The billets were homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h, then hot rolled to 4 mm through seven passes with the finish rolling temperature of about 820 °C, and subsequently air cooled to 660 °C, followed by cooling inside the furnace to simulate coiling. The hot-rolled plates were cold rolled to 1 mm after acid pickling. Tensile specimens with a gauge portion of 12.5 mm in width, 1 mm in thickness and 25 mm in length were machined with longitudinal axis parallel to the rolling direction.  Some cold-rolled samples were heated to 810 °C for ~2 s in a resistance furnace, which is referred as non-isothermal annealing process. Subsequently, all the samples were quenched to 310 °C in salt bath and isothermal held for 500 s. Finally, the samples after heat treatment were water quenched to ambient temperature.

Table_topic: Table II Hardness and Tensile Properties of the Experimental Steels
Text: The present work thus, aimed at production of fine-grained, low-carbon bainitic steels with high strength and toughness through industry-friendly conventional hot-rolling and air-cooling routes without the necessity of tempering treatment. Three experimental heats of 25 kg each were made in a Inductotherm laboratory air induction furnace with varying alloying combinations. The cast cylindrical ingots were 100 mm in diameter. The defective portion comprising about 25 pct from top and 10 pct from bottom of the ingots was discarded. The trimmed ingots were heated to 1373 K (1100 °C) and soaked for 3 hours. After soaking, the ingots were hot-rolled into 20-mm-thick plates in a HILLE, UK 2-Hi experimental rolling mill. Samples for dilatometry and hot compression studies were prepared from the as-rolled plates. After determining the optimum process parameters for obtaining the desired microstructural morphology of the steels, the plates were further rolled into 6-mm plates in three passes with the final rolling temperature (FRT) of 1173 K (900 °C) followed by air cooling (AC).

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the as-received TRIP samples.
Text: The steel was melted in a 50 kg vacuum furnace and cast as ingot. The ingot was subsequently forged into a rectangular slab of size 150 × 100 × 30 mm. The slab was reheated to 1200 °C for 2 h, followed by three passes hot-rolled with the thickness reduction of 33%, 25% and 27% in each pass, respectively. The rods of size 10 mm dia x 70 mm were used for equal channel angular pressing (ECAP) from the hot rolled plate.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the as-received TRIP samples.
Text: The steel was melted in a 50 kg vacuum furnace and cast as ingot. The ingot was subsequently forged into a rectangular slab of size 150 × 100 × 30 mm. The slab was reheated to 1200 °C for 2 h, followed by three passes hot-rolled with the thickness reduction of 33%, 25% and 27% in each pass, respectively. The rods of size 10 mm dia x 70 mm were used for equal channel angular pressing (ECAP) from the hot rolled plate. 1 pass ECAP was conducted at 400 °C by using route C (which in the next pass of ECAP was rotated 180° around the rod's longitudinal axis) with a 50 MPa squeeze pressure and the squeeze speed was 5 mm/min. After ECAP, the rods were processed into tensile specimens with a width of 3 mm and a length of 10 mm. Two stage salt bath heat treatment was applied to the ECAPed samples. First, the strip was annealed at 800 °C for 5 min, and then quenched to the isothermal bainitic transformation (IBT) temperature at 400 °C for 3 min, followed by cooling in air to room temperature. Subsequently, the slices were manually thinned to 30 μm and punched into 3 mm dia disks.

Table_topic: Tensile results of hot-rolled experimental steel samples.
Text: Two experimental steel ingots (AL and TM) were melted in a 10-kg vacuum induction furnace, and their chemical compositions were determined as shown in Table 1 . TM steel was deoxidized by Ti-Mg to obtain fine Ti-Mg oxide inclusions. A common Nb-microalloyed low carbon steel was deoxidized by Al for comparison (AL). The experimental steel ingots were reheated to 1250 °C and held for 30 min, then rolled to 12-mm-thick plates with a final rolling temperature about 1050 °C. The hot-rolled plates were cooled to 600 °C at ~15 °C/s by a water jet device, and then air cooled to room temperature. Cylinder samples of ∅3 mm × 10 mm were machined from the hot-rolled plates, and the thermal simulation experiment was carried out on L78 Rita full-automatic transformation equipment. The samples were held at 1050 °C, 1150 °C, 1250 °C, and 1320 °C for 300 s, cooled to 900 °C at 10 °C/s, and then cooled to room temperature at 2 °C/s. For the measurement of austenite grain size, samples were heated to 1050 °C, 1150 °C, 1250 °C, and 1320 °C, holding 300s and then water quenching to room temperature.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of tested steels.
Text: These steels have been widely used to fabricate large engineering structures such as oil storage tanks, ships and pressure vessels because of their desirable combination of mechanical properties, such as high strength and toughness, as well as good weldability. Two HSLA steel plates, one deoxidized using Zr-Ti based agents with an overall composition of 0.01-0.02wt% and the other deoxidized by adding 0.025wt% Al, were made in an industrial scale. Ca treatment was carried out at the final stage of liquid steel for both steels. The precise chemical composition of these two steels in tundish is listed in Table 1. Both of them were virtually identical produced by vacuum-refined, continuously cast, thermo-mechanical control processed and tempered at 550°C for several hours to obtain high strength and excellent toughness combination.

Table_topic: The mechanical properties of the investigated steel by different heat treatments.
Text: To prepare the DSC sample, a slice of about 0.2mm in thickness was cut from the electroslag casting rod. The heat treatment specimens with size of 15mm×15mm×80mm were cut from the half of radius in the steel rod. All the specimens were heated to 1000°C in an electric resistance furnace for 45min, followed by oil quenching (OQ). Table_topic: Tensile properties of tested steels.
Text: The ingots were forged into slabs. The 40mm thick slabs were heated to 1200°C, and held at that temperature for 1h for the dissolution of microalloyed elements, then air-cooled to 920°C. The slabs were then rolled into steel plates with 7mm thickness after seven passes on the φ450mm trial rolling mill. The end temperature of finishing roll was controlled to 820°C. Plate A was watercooled at a cooling rates of 13°C/s, and then coiled at 650°C.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of tested steels.

Table_topic: The mechanical characteristics of the present TWIP steels at room temperature.
Text: For this purpose, Cu was added to the Fe-20Mn-1.3C base composition. The ingots of three grades TWIP steels with the different Cu contents, i.e. Fe-20Mn-1.3C, Fe-20Mn-1.5Cu-1.3C and Fe-20Mn-3.0Cu-1.3C in wt.% (the 0 Cu, 1.5 Cu and 3.0 Cu TWIP steel, respectively), were prepared by vacuum induction melting. After austenite annealed at 1050°C for 4.5h, the cast ingots were hot rolled to the plate of 3mm thickness: hot rolling temperature was 900°C. The hot-rolled sheets were cold rolled to 1.2mm thick sheets and subsequently solution treated at 1050°C for 4.5h for 20min prior to water quenched. The chemical compositions of the three steels are listed in Table 1 . The tensile tests were performed according to Chinese Standard GB/T 228-2002 . The tensile samples were cut out of the sheets parallel to the transverse direction and conducted at room temperature by applying a strain rate of 10-4 s-1. In the initial state before deformation at room temperature, X-ray analysis (Fig. 1 a) revealed that all steels were fully austenitic after solution treatment followed by water quenching. The microstructure of the annealed sample before tensile test was fully austenitic, and the mean grain size of all the steels is 41±2μm, when annealing twin boundaries were considered in the grain size measurement. The mechanical characteristics of present TWIP steels are shown in Table 2 . Microstructures of the Fe-20Mn-3.0Cu-1.3C TWIP steel deformed to different strain levels are presented in Fig. 5 . Three fully austenitic experimental high-carbon TWIP steel grades, differing in their content of Cu were produced and the stacking fault energies of the TWIP steels increased from ~24.36 to 28.74mJm-2 on the addition of 3.0wt.% Cu.

Table_topic: Table II Mechanical Properties of the Experimental UHS Steel Austenitized at 1173 K (900 °C) for Different Tempering Conditions
Text: The microstructure of these steels in the as-quenched condition consists essentially of lath martensite. The samples had been austenitized at 1173 K (900 °C) for 1 hour, followed by oil quenching, subjected to refrigeration in LN2 for 2 hours, and subsequently tempered at 758 K (485 °C) for 4 and 8 hours. The steel under investigation was produced in a 40-kg batch by vacuum induction melting of electrolytically pure raw materials and pouring, under vacuum, into a rectangular mold of 100 × 300 mm cross section. The resultant ingot was homogenized at 1323 K (1050 °C) for 24 hours and subsequently radiographed, and the defective "pipe" portions were removed. The sound portion of the ingot was soaked at 1323 K (1050 °C) for 4 hours and hot-rolled into 15-mm-thick plates. Samples for heat treatment were cut from the rolled plate, austenitized at 1173 K (900 °C) for 1 hour, oil quenched to room temperature, and subsequently LN2 treated to minimize retained austenite. The samples were then subjected to tempering at different temperatures, viz., 758 K (485 °C) for either 4 hours, followed by quenching in oil.

The samples had been austenitized at 1173 K (900 °C) for 1 hour, followed by oil quenching, subjected to refrigeration in LN2 for 2 hours, and subsequently tempered at 758 K (485 °C) for 4 and 8 hours. The steel under investigation was produced in a 40-kg batch by vacuum induction melting of electrolytically pure raw materials and pouring, under vacuum, into a rectangular mold of 100 × 300 mm cross section. The resultant ingot was homogenized at 1323 K (1050 °C) for 24 hours and subsequently radiographed, and the defective "pipe" portions were removed. The sound portion of the ingot was soaked at 1323 K (1050 °C) for 4 hours and hot-rolled into 15-mm-thick plates. Samples for heat treatment were cut from the rolled plate, austenitized at 1173 K (900 °C) for 1 hour, oil quenched to room temperature, and subsequently LN2 treated to minimize retained austenite. The samples were then subjected to tempering at different temperatures, viz., 758 K (485 °C) for either 8 hours, followed by quenching in oil.

Table_topic: Table 2 The mechanical properties of the samples after different heat treatment processes
Text: The original material was produced in open-hearth furnace, then refined in vacuum refinery furnace, and cast into ingots of 60 mm diameter. The ingots were reheated to 1200 °C, held for 3 h, and forged into the bars about 16 mm diameter. The forged bars were cooled to room temperature in air. After forging, the forged bars were spheroidize annealed. During the spheroidizing annealing process, the specimens were heated to 800 °C, held for 2 h, and cooled to 720 °C, held for 3 h, then cooled to 250 °C in furnace, and finally cooled to room temperature in air. The specimens were reheated to 1200 °C, then cooled to 750-1150 °C. In order to observe the microstructure after the dynamic recrystallization, the 0.22-1.0 single compressive deformation with the strain rate of 0.1-10 s-1 was carried out immediately followed by cooling to room temperature in water. The specimen were held 10-90 s at same temperature after deformation, then cooled to room temperature in water in order to observe the microstructure after static recrystallization. For ausforging-and-tempering experiments, the ingot was ausenitized at 1100 °C, and forged at temperatures ranging from 1000 to 800 °C, then quenched in oil directly. After ausforging, the specimens were tempered at temperatures ranging from 600 °C for 5 h.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of IF steels for pilot hot-rolled sheet
Text: These were prepared by a laboratory vacuum induction melting. Laboratory melt ingots were hot-rolled to plate with 20mm thickness. The specimens for pilot hot strip rolling test were obtained in the form of square as-cast slab with 30mm thickness, 150mm width and 300mm length. Samples were reheated to 1200°C at 5°Cs-1 and hold for 2min using direct resistance heating system inside the furnace ( - ). Specimens were then cooled to the isothermal test temperature. The slab was fed into the pilot rolling mill after being homogenized in a furnace at 1200°C. Slab with 25mm in thickness was passed through five passes to produce 3.2mm thick sheet. The finishing rolling temperature was about 900°C. After rolling, the hot bands were cooled to 600°C by water cooling system and then furnace-cooled to simulate coiling process of hot strip mill. The tensile flat specimens with a gauge section of 50mm in length and 25mm in width were machined.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the investigated steel.
Text: In this study, the experimental steel was prepared as a vacuum-melted 40Kg ingot. The ingot was reheated to 1200°C and hot-rolled to a thickness of 4mm. The finish temperature is approximately 860°C, followed by coiling at 600°C. After cold rolling to a thickness of 1mm, a two-stage salt bath heat treatment was adopted. Intercritical annealing (IA) was done at 830°C for 1min. In order to control the morphology of bainite, the isothermal bainitic transformation (IBT) temperature was kept the same for all treatments following. The material was subsequently fast quenched and austempered at 440°C for 3min, followed by cooling in air.

Table_topic: Table III Tensile Properties at Room Temperature and 253 K (−20 °C) of the Specimens
Text: In this study, plate-type two API X80 pipeline steels having different distributions of hard phases and elongated grains along the rolling direction were fabricated by controlling a carbon content and hot rolling process. The steels used in this study were API X80 pipeline steels (minimum yield strength level; 615 MPa), and their chemical compositions are shown in Table I. An overall grain refinement effect was expected by rolling with a high rolling reduction ratio of 80 pct in the non-recrystallized region of austenite after austenitization at 1453 K (1180 °C) for 2 hours. Rolling was finished at 1155 K (782 °C) in the austenite region above Ar3. After the finish rolling, the steels were rapidly cooled to finish cooling temperature of 785 K (512 °C) at the cooling speed ranging from 15 to 20 K/s, and then were cooled in the air, to room temperature. Specimens were machined in 90 deg to the rolling direction of the steel plates, which are the directions for guarantees of mechanical properties of the UOE and the spiral pipes. For convenience, these four specimens are referred to as ‘A90', ‘A30', ‘B90', and ‘B30' according to the carbon content and the direction.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the investigate steels subjected to various processing conditions.
Text: A laboratory scale 25kVA air induction furnace was used to manufacture the steel with the chemical composition as shown in Table 1. After cropping the top section of the ingot containing shrinkage/pipes, the remaining portion of 200mm×50mm×50mm size was hot forged down to about 19mm×19mm cross section. After that, the Ac1, Ac3 and MS temperatures were measured as 725°C, 830°C and 365°C respectively, by a Gleeble 1500D LVDT type dilatometer using cylindrical hollow samples of 1mm wall thickness. At first the samples were heated at a heating rate of 10°C/s at 1000°C and soaked for 5min, and then cooled under constant rate of 20°C/s to room temperature. The forged bars were soaked at 1200°C and subsequently subjected to TMCP with 750°C finish rolling temperature (FRT) according to the laboratory scale schedule as mention in Fig. 2 using two-high rolling mill (10 HP) and finally the rolled plates (≈8mm) were allowed to air cooling (AC).

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the investigate steels subjected to various processing conditions.
Text: A laboratory scale 25kVA air induction furnace was used to manufacture the steel with the chemical composition as shown in Table 1. After cropping the top section of the ingot containing shrinkage/pipes, the remaining portion of 200mm×50mm×50mm size was hot forged down to about 19mm×19mm cross section. After that, the Ac1, Ac3 and MS temperatures were measured as 725°C, 830°C and 365°C respectively, by a Gleeble 1500D LVDT type dilatometer using cylindrical hollow samples of 1mm wall thickness. At first the samples were heated at a heating rate of 10°C/s at 1000°C and soaked for 5min, and then cooled under constant rate of 20°C/s to room temperature. The forged bars were soaked at 1200°C and subsequently subjected to TMCP with 750°C finish rolling temperature (FRT) according to the laboratory scale schedule as mention in Fig. 2 using two-high rolling mill (10 HP) and finally the rolled plates (≈8mm) were allowed to air cooling (AC). The TMCP samples were treated by Q&P processes, as shown in Fig. 3. All samples were subjected to partial austenitisation (PA) at 800°C temperatures with the same holding time of 30min, followed by rapid quenching in a salt bath maintained at 345°C below MS temperature (365°C) and partitioning at the same temperature for 30min.

Table_topic: Table 3 Mechanical properties of test pieces in tensile testing
Text: Dog-bone shaped test pieces were cut from low carbon steel sheets with an initial thickness of 6 mm. The thickness was reduced to 2 mm by machining. Table 1 shows the chemical composition of the test pieces used in this study. The test pieces were heat treated in an argon atmosphere at 450 °C for 1.5 h and 700 °C for 10 h and then allowed to cool to room temperature in the furnace. These two heat treatments were used to reduce the dislocation density and to change the microstructure of the pearlite phase.

Table_topic: Table 3 Mechanical properties of test pieces in tensile testing
Text: Dog-bone shaped test pieces were cut from low carbon steel sheets with an initial thickness of 6 mm. The thickness was reduced to 2 mm by machining. Table 1 shows the chemical composition of the test pieces used in this study. The test pieces were heat treated in an argon atmosphere at 450 °C for 1.5 h and 700 °C for 10 h and then allowed to cool to room temperature in the furnace. These two heat treatments were used to reduce the dislocation density and to change the microstructure of the pearlite phase. In this study, test pieces subjected to heat treatments of 450 °C are denoted by TP450 . Although the heat treatments were carried out in an argon atmosphere, TP450 were wrapped in aluminum and titanium foil, respectively, in order to minimize the possibility of oxide formation.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of two steels at ambient temperature.
Text: The matrix alloy used in this work was a commercial 304 austenitic stainless steel (304SS), which chemical composition was given in Table 1 . For the production of in situ 5vol.% TiC particulate reinforced austenitic stainless (TiC-304SS), 304SS ingot, titanium powders, graphite powders and iron powders were used to be the raw materials. After the matrix alloy 304SS had been melted in a medium frequency vacuum induction melting (VIM) furnace at 1873-1923K, the preformed blocks were introduced into the melt. The ingots with 50mm in diameter were hot forged at 1273K into 15mm-thick bars. For comparison, 304SS without TiC addition was also cast and machined into the same dimensions and tested under the same conditions as the above sample, and properties test were also carried out under the same conditions. All of samples for mechanical testing and microstructure observation were cut by electric spark machining from the forged bars. Some samples were heated at 1323K for 40min then quenched in water. The static oxidation tests were carried out in a box furnace at 1073K. The samples with size of 20mm×15mm×2mm were placed in the furnace in individual pre-annealed alumina crucible and oxidized in static air.

Table_topic: The overview of the mechanical properties of the investigated TWIP steels with various Mn and Al content. SFE values were calculated based on the thermodynamic model proposed by Saeed-Akbari et al. [15].
Text: Slabs taken from vacuum cast ingots were solution-treated at 1200°C for 2h and hot-rolled to a thickness of 2.5mm, prior to cold-rolling to a thickness of 1.25mm. Recrystallization annealing was carried out at 800°C for 100s. All the steels had a fully recrystallized austenitic microstructure consisting of equiaxed grains, some of which containing annealing twins. ASTM E8 standard samples of the annealed steels were machined with their long axis aligned with the rolling direction (RD). In order to remove the deformation-affected surface layer on the samples, about 100μm of thickness was removed from the surface by electrolytic polishing. The overview of the mechanical properties of the investigated Fe-xMn-0.6C-yAl steels is presented in Table 2.

Table_topic: The overview of the mechanical properties of the investigated TWIP steels with various Mn and Al content. SFE values were calculated based on the thermodynamic model proposed by Saeed-Akbari et al. [15].
Text: Slabs taken from vacuum cast ingots were solution-treated at 1200°C for 2h and hot-rolled to a thickness of 2.5mm, prior to cold-rolling to a thickness of 1.25mm. Recrystallization annealing was carried out at 800°C for 100s. All the steels had a fully recrystallized austenitic microstructure consisting of equiaxed grains, some of which containing annealing twins. ASTM E8 standard samples of the annealed steels were machined with their long axis aligned with the rolling direction (RD). In order to remove the deformation-affected surface layer on the samples, about 100μm of thickness was removed from the surface by electrolytic polishing. The overview of the mechanical properties of the investigated Fe-xMn-0.6C-yAl steels is presented in Table 2.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the hot rolled plates produced in different cooling modes.
Text: Quenching and tempering (QT) is the conventional process to produce high strength and toughness in these steels . Table 1 shows the chemical composition of the extremely low carbon Cu bearing steel. The steel was melted in the vacuum induction furnace and cast into a 40kg ingot, which was then hot forged and cut into billets with the dimension of 80mm×80mm×100mm. The slab was homogenized at 1100°C for 120min. Using a two-high 450mm pilot mill, a two-stage hot rolling was carried out where the respective rolling reduction (RR) was 55% and 58%. The finish rolling temperature was set to be 800°C. For the cooling stage, the slab was first water cooled to 680°C. Two cooling modes were subsequently employed: Process A (furnace cooled to 600°C and then air cooled to room temperature). Then, a twin-jet electropolishing was carried out using a mixture of 87.5% absolute ethyl alcohol and 12.5% perchloric acid at -30°C and potential of 30V.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the samples treated by different heat treatment process.
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace. After casting, the ingots were homogenized at 1200°C for 180min, and then hot forged into a billet with a dimension of 25mm×65mm×800mm. The Ms point of the experimental steel was measured as 350°C by a HF-PJ-14 thermal dilatometer, using 6mm diameter×30mm cylindrical specimen. The specimen was firstly heated to 920°C at a heating rate of 10°Cs-1, held at this temperature for 10min, and then cooled to room temperature at a cooling rate of 60°Cs-1. All the samples were firstly heated to 900°C for 20min for full austenitization, followed by different cooling processes. For Q&T process, after austenitized at 900°C, the samples were quenched directly by oil to room temperature to obtain the full martensite.All samples treated by Q&T and B-QP processes were tempered at 260°C for 2h. In order to easily examine the volume fraction of bainite after isothermally held at 370°C for different time, the samples were directly quenched by water to room temperature without tempering.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the samples treated by different heat treatment process.
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace. After casting, the ingots were homogenized at 1200°C for 180min, and then hot forged into a billet with a dimension of 25mm×65mm×800mm. The Ms point of the experimental steel was measured as 350°C by a HF-PJ-14 thermal dilatometer, using 6mm diameter×30mm cylindrical specimen. The specimen was firstly heated to 920°C at a heating rate of 10°Cs-1, held at this temperature for 10min, and then cooled to room temperature at a cooling rate of 60°Cs-1. All the samples were firstly heated to 900°C for 20min for full austenitization, followed by different cooling processes. For B-QP processes, samples denoted as B3-QP were initially quenched into salt bath at 370°C, isothermally holding for 3min in salt bath respectively in order to obtain different contents of bainite. Then the samples were immediately transferred into another salt bath at 220°C for 30min for carbon partitioning and finally cooled to ambient temperature in air. All samples treated by Q&T and B-QP processes were tempered at 260°C for 2h. In order to easily examine the volume fraction of bainite after isothermally held at 370°C for different time, the samples were directly quenched by water to room temperature without tempering.

Table_topic: Table III Tensile Properties of the Steels Under the Untreated and Heat-Treated Conditions
Text: The industrial heat treatments performed in wheel production are rim chilling and tempering. At the end of the rim chilling, the wheel is tempered at 500 °C for 5 hours, followed by air-cooling to room temperature. All the specimens were taken from the wheels after the industrial heat treatments. Then, several samples were heat treated at various temperatures to reproduce the modification of the microstructure due to the shoe braking.

Table_topic: Table III Tensile Properties of the Steels Under the Untreated and Heat-Treated Conditions
Text: The industrial heat treatments performed in wheel production are rim chilling and tempering. At the end of the rim chilling, the wheel is tempered at 500 °C for 5 hours, followed by air-cooling to room temperature. All the specimens were taken from the wheels after the industrial heat treatments. Then, several samples were heat treated at various temperatures to reproduce the modification of the microstructure due to the shoe braking. The specimens were heated to the chosen temperature with a rate of 40 °C/h, maintained at this temperature for 45 minutes, and then air-cooled to room temperature in order to obtain a uniform microstructure. The temperatures of 700 °C were chosen as representative of each temperature range, imposing heating-cooling heat treatments on wheel specimens so as to obtain the same microstructure that was observed in shoe-braked wheels.

Table_topic: Table III Tensile and Charpy Notch Toughness, Effective Grain Size, and Cleavage Facet Size of the Bainitic Steels
Text: After the austenitization at 1423 K (1150 °C) for 1 hour, rolling was started at approximately 1353 K (1080 °C) and finished in the austenite region above Ar3 (1123 K). An overall grain refinement effect was expected by rolling with a high rolling reduction ratio (88 pct) in the nonrecrystallized region of austenite, and the plate thickness was reduced from 100 mm to 12 mm. The rolled plates were air cooled down to the start cooling temperature of 873 K (600 °C) at a cooling rate of 0.1 K/s, and then they were water cooled at a cooling rate of 20 K/s to room temperature.

An overall grain refinement effect was expected by rolling with a high rolling reduction ratio (88 pct) in the nonrecrystallized region of austenite,[4] and the plate thickness was reduced from 100 mm to 12 mm. In some plates, the cooling rate was changed to 0.1 K/s at 673 K (400 °C) to promote the formation of acicular ferrite.

Table_topic: Summary of room-temperature tensile properties of all tested specimens.
Text: The steel ingot, prepared by vacuum melting and casting, was rough rolled to a 40 mm thickness. The rough-rolled plate was then heated to 1250 °C for 120 min to reach a full austenization. Afterwards, the plate was hot-rolled to a 5 mm thickness through five passes followed by air-cooling to about 400 °C and then isothermal holding for 60 min. Here, the finish rolling temperature (FRT) was controlled to be about 850 ± 5 °C. Finally, the steel was furnace cooled to room temperature. The specimens deformed along the rolling direction (RD).

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the WQ and aged HSLA-100 steel
Text: It may be noted that C is kept at a very low level to improve the weldability, and a substantially high content of Ni is provided for increasing the hardenability and improving the hot workability of the steel. The material was available in the form of flat plates from which blanks were machined with their axes oriented along the rolling direction for the fabrication of tensile and fracture specimens. These were austenised for 1h at 910°C and water quenched (WQ).

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the WQ and aged HSLA-100 steel
Text: It may be noted that C is kept at a very low level to improve the weldability, and a substantially high content of Ni is provided for increasing the hardenability and improving the hot workability of the steel. Text: The strips were cold rolled at room temperature to 90% reduction in thickness in a pilot plant and austenite transformed into martensite. Next, the samples were placed in a furnace under argon atmosphere for isothermal annealing at 900°C for 2min to obtain complete reversion to austenite from deformed martensite and the average grain size of austenite was in the UFG regime. Table_topic: Mechanical properties of TiC-reinforced and conventional low-alloy abrasion-resistant steels.
Text: The chemical compositions of the experimental steels are listed in Table 1 . The TiC-reinforced steels were melted via a 150 kg vacuum melting furnace and forged into 100 mm × 100 mm × 120 mm ingots. First, square billets were heated to 1200 °C for solution treatment (3 h) in a box resistance furnace. Then, the square billets were rolled to 12 mm plates by two-step controlled rolling and ultrafast (~100 °C/s) cooling to room temperature. Finally, the plates were treated by a two-step heat treatment. First, the plates were tempered at 650 °C for 3 h and air-cooled. Then, they were fully austenitized at 880 °C for 20 min and immediately water-quenched to room temperature.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of SAE-1040 and -4340 steels.
Text: Two types of steels, namely SAE-1040 (C-Mn steel) and SAE-4340 (Cr-Ni-Mo steel), supplied in the form of 50mm diameters rods, from which both materials were cut into three equal pieces 100mm long using hack saw with lubricant to avoid excessive heating. Table 1 presents the average chemical composition of these steels in wt.% after three runs for each type using spectroscopic chemical analyzer. Both materials were subjected simultaneously to the same heat treatment type in an electric resistance furnace. The first treatment was austenitizing at 850°C for 2h followed by furnace cooling (full annealing).

Table_topic: Table II Tensile Properties of the Selected Steels at Quasi-Static Rate
Text: The annealing process included (i) the conventional continuous annealing line process used in steel industry for producing DP590 grade steel (CAL). In CAL, the specimens were heated to 790 °C (1063.15 °K) at 10 deg/s followed by the isothermal holding of 60 seconds at this temperature. The first stage was free cooling from 790 °C (1063.15 °K) to 675 °C (948.15 °K) for austenite enrichment with carbon. The third stage was holding at 275 °C (548.15 °K) for 120 seconds for the tempering of transformed martensite and finally quenching to room temperature. The three DP steels with different microstructure morphologies were subjected to tensile deformation at high strain rates (100 to 650/s).

Table_topic: Table II Tensile Properties of the Selected Steels at Quasi-Static Rate
Text: The annealing process included (ii) the continuous heating and cooling resulting in modified DP microstructure (CHCL). In the first stage, heating was continued up to 710 °C (983.15 °K) at a heating rate of 5 deg/s. In the second stage, the slower heating rate of 1 deg/s was employed to reach 790 °C (1063.15 °K). In the third stage, heating to 840 °C (1113.15 °K) was conducted at a heating rate of 2 deg/s. Finally, the cooling route similar to that of CAL process was followed. The metallurgical attributes by which the resultant DP microstructure was obtained in CHCL are discussed elsewhere. The objective of CAS process was to obtain core- and shell-like DP microstructure having martensite packets surrounded by three-dimensional ferrite network/channel. The underlying phenomenon of the evolution of such microstructure for CAS process, as shown in Figure 1, is reported elsewhere.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of experimental steels and other steels used for comparison.
Text: A 100 kg ingot was cast using a vacuum furnace and hot forged into billets with transverse dimension of 60 mm × 30 mm. Prior to rolling, dilatometry experiment was carried out using DIL805 A/D dilatometer to investigate the feasibility of introduction of ferrite and to define TMCP parameters. The cylindrical samples of dimensions φ 5 mm × 10 mm were prepared from billets. After homogenization at 1200 °C for 3 min, the samples were air-cooled to 1050 °C for first compression (true strain of 0.18 and strain rate of 1 s-1), and then air-cooled to specific temperature (900/850/800/750/720 °C) for second compression (true strain of 0.47 and strain rate of 1 s-1). This was followed by air cooling of samples at a rate of 5 °C/s to room temperature. A sample without deformation at 1200 °C was directly air-cooled to room temperature for comparison. Fig. 1 illustrates the schematic of TMCP. 30 mm thick billets were reheated to 1200 °C for 2 h, followed by two stage controlled rolling using a laboratory rolling mill. First, the billets were rolled to an intermediate thickness of 12 mm via 3 passes. After air cooling to specific temperature (860 °C), the intermediate billets were rolled to 3 mm thick sheets via 5 passes. For comparison, the sheet with secondary rolling temperature of 750 °C was air-cooled directly to room temperature after rolling.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of as-cast low-alloyed high strength steels by different heat treatment paths.
Text: The specimens with the size of 11mm×11mm×70mm for heat treatments were obtained from the radius in half of the as-cast ingot. All the specimens were heated in a box-type electric resistance furnace at 950°C, followed by water quenching. After that, the specimens were reheated to 800°C and then quenched to water, and finally tempered at 500°C. The details of heat treatment processes used in this investigation are described in Fig. 1 . For further microstructural analysis, several slices about 0.35mm thickness were cut by wire-electrode cutting, followed by thinning to a thickness of about 0.04-0.05mm through mechanical method.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of as-cast low-alloyed high strength steels by different heat treatment paths.
Text: The specimens with the size of 11mm×11mm×70mm for heat treatments were obtained from the radius in half of the as-cast ingot. All the specimens were heated in a box-type electric resistance furnace at 950°C, followed by water quenching. After that, the specimens were reheated to 800°C and then cooled in the air, and finally tempered at 500°C. The details of heat treatment processes used in this investigation are described in Fig. 1 . For further microstructural analysis, several slices about 0.35mm thickness were cut by wire-electrode cutting, followed by thinning to a thickness of about 0.04-0.05mm through mechanical method.

This hardened steel bar was then tempered at 300°C for 1h followed by air cooling.

Table_topic: Results of mechanical properties after different heat treatment processes
Text: The chemical composition of the experimental steel in this study is listed in Table 1. The casting ingots were melted in a vacuum induction furnace. After casting, the ingots were homogenized at 1200°C for 180min, and then hot forged into a billet with a width of 65mm and a thickness of 25mm. The samples were firstly heated at a heating rate of 10°C/s to 920°C and then held for 10min, followed by cooling to room temperature at a cooling rate of 60°C/s. The samples were treated by the Q&P and Q-DP processes, as shown in Fig. 2. All samples were austenitized at 900°C for 20min, followed by salt bath quenching to a targeted temperature. For the Q&P process, samples were quenched to 250 °C in a salt bath for 5min, and then transferred into another salt bath at 320°C for 40min and finally cooled down to ambient temperature in air. In order to relieve the residual stresses formed during air quenching stage, all samples were tempered at 280°C for 120min.

Table_topic: Results of mechanical properties after different heat treatment processes
Text: The chemical composition of the experimental steel in this study is listed in Table 1. The casting ingots were melted in a vacuum induction furnace. After casting, the ingots were homogenized at 1200°C for 180min, and then hot forged into a billet with a width of 65mm and a thickness of 25mm. The samples were firstly heated at a heating rate of 10°C/s to 920°C and then held for 10min, followed by cooling to room temperature at a cooling rate of 60°C/s. The samples were treated by the Q&P and Q-DP processes, as shown in Fig. 2. All samples were austenitized at 900°C for 20min, followed by salt bath quenching to a targeted temperature. For the Q&P process, samples were quenched to 250 °C in a salt bath for 5min, and then transferred into another salt bath at 320°C for 40min and finally cooled down to ambient temperature in air. For the Q-DP processes, samples were quenched to 190°C for 5min, respectively, followed by immediately transferred into another salt bath with dynamic start partitioning temperature of 320°C, then those samples were continuously cooled from 320°C to 260°C in 40min and eventually quenched by air. In order to relieve the residual stresses formed during air quenching stage, all samples were tempered at 280°C for 120min.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of tested steels.
Text: To reveal prior austenite grain boundaries, the samples were austenitized at 860°C for 0.5h followed by water quenching. In this study, the wheel rim was austenitized at 860°C, cooled with a water spray and then tempered at 500°C. Then, the martensite is tempered at 500°C. The microstructure of wheel steel is composed of proeutectoid ferrite and pearlite.
