Table_topic: Mechanical properties of A75-A80 steels.
Text: Thus, 2wt% Al was added in the experimental steel, which is different from the composition of traditional TRIP steel. Liquid steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace of capacity ~50kg. The liquid steel was poured into a pre-heated tundish (1200°C) and then allowed to flow into the cast rollers using a hole-type nozzle. Lastly, the as-cast strip was cooled to room temperature by water after strip casting. The thickness of the as-cast strip was measured to be ~2.2mm. The as-cast strip was cut into small samples for subsequent processing. The as-cast strip samples were heated to 700-800°C for 10min, followed by water quenching. For convenience, the as-cast strip samples heat treated at 780 °C are referred as H78. Next, H78 steels were cold rolled to 0.8mm (64% reduction). In the end, the cold-rolled sheet samples of H78 steel were annealed at 750°C for 5min, followed by direct water quenching.

Table_topic: Tensile results of salt-baths heat treated CMnSi cold-rolled samples
Text: The CMnSi TRIP-aided was prepared as a 50kg ingot in an air induction furnace. The cast ingot was forged into a 300×150×50mm block. Small blocks of 120×120×50mm were cut from forged stock. These 50mm thick blocks were soaked at 1175°C for 1h, and hot rolled to a thickness of 3.2mm in eight passes. Hot rolled plates were annealed at 900°C for 1h to reduce the hardness for easier cold rolling. The hot-rolled air annealed steel plates were pickled in a 25vol.% HCl solution and subsequently cold rolled to achieve a final thickness of 1mm.

Table_topic: Tensile properties for 18Cr-8Ni stainless steel and 30% CR, 60% CR and 90% CR samples after annealing for various time.
Text: The experimental material used in this study was commercial 18Cr-8Ni cold-rolled stainless steel strips of ~3 mm thickness and the chemical composition (weight percent) of this steel is listed in Table 1 . The strips were cold rolled in a pilot plant to 30% reduction in thickness at room temperature. The objective of changing cold rolling reduction was to obtain microstructures with different content of strain-induced martensite and deformed untransformed austenite in samples. Next, the strips were isothermally annealed at a temperature of 900 °C for 1 min in a tubular resistance furnace under argon atmosphere, and then subsequently quenched in ice-water.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of experimental steels.
Text: The ultra-low carbon and medium-manganese steels were prepared in a high frequency induction furnace in a vacuum atmosphere. 150 kg ingot was forged into rectangular billet of thickness ~140 mm. Hot rolling and heat treatment process is illustrated in Fig. 1 . The 140 mm thick slab was heated to 1200 °C for 2 h and then hot rolled to 100 mm with start and finish temperature of 980 °C and 935 °C, respectively, involving 5 passes. Total rolling reduction ratio (initial thickness/finial thickness) was 1.4 and is lower than the conventional ultra-heavy plate that exceeds 3.0, because deformation was introduced into the core of plate to refine the prior austenite grain size . Subsequently, the heavy plate was directly water-quenched to room temperature, using an accelerated cooling system to obtain martensitic microstructure. The cooling rates at t/4 during direct quenching process was ~1.5 °C/s and was measured by thermocouple. After water quenching, the heavy plates were intercritically annealed for 30 min at 630 °C, between the two phase region (α+γ). Finally, the heavy plates were air cooled to room temperature.

The actual chemical composition is listed in Table 1 . Fig. 1c shows that the as-received samples are heated to 600 °C for 30 min and then water quenched to room temperature (RT).

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of microalloyed steel processed using different cooling path.
Text: Ingots of the experimental steel were forged to 100mm in length, 90mm in width and 90mm in thickness. After austenitizing at 1200°C for 2h, hot rolling was carried out on a φ450mm experimental hot mill, with the finish rolling temperature of 900°C. The complete continuous laminar cooling (ACC) and continuous ultra-fast cooling (UFC) route was a labeled as 1# , with a cooling rate ~12°C/s. Steels were finish rolled at (T f ) 900°C, cooled to the coiling temperature of 615°C by either of the three routes (1#, 2#, 3#), and subsequently cooled in the furnace to simulate the coiling process with a cooling rate of ~0.014°C/s.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of microalloyed steel processed using different cooling path.
Text: Ingots of the experimental steel were forged to 100mm in length, 90mm in width and 90mm in thickness. After austenitizing at 1200°C for 2h, hot rolling was carried out on a φ450mm experimental hot mill, with the finish rolling temperature of 900°C. Here, the steel is cooled by UFC to T stop (ultra fast cooling stop temperature) of 750°C and cooled to T coil (coiling temperature) with a cooling rate of ~12°C/s. Steels were finish rolled at (T f ) 900°C, cooled to the coiling temperature of 615°C by either of the three routes (1#, 2#, 3#), and subsequently cooled in the furnace to simulate the coiling process with a cooling rate of ~0.014°C/s.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the studied 18Cr-2Mo steels.
Text: The 18Cr-2Mo FSSs used in this study were melted in a 50kg vacuum induction furnace. The casting ingots with a diameter of 120mm were hot forged into the size of 30mm×250mm×200mm (thickness×width×length), hot rolled into 6mm plate, and annealed at 950°C for 30min, followed by cooling in the air. The chemical compositions of the 18Cr-2Mo steels measured are listed in Table 1 .

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the investigated samples.
Text: A small block (20mm×15mm×10mm) was cut from an ‘As-received' plate and was subjected to 15 pass deformation schedule in plane-strain compression mode inside Gleeble 3500® simulator with true strain of 0.1 per pass starting from 1125°C down to 775°C with an interval of 25°C at the cooling rate of 1°C/s, Fig. 1(a). Blocks of 200mm×125mm×25mm size taken out from the As-received plates were subjected to soaking treatment (1130°C for 1h) .

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the investigated samples.
Text: A small block (20mm×15mm×10mm) was cut from an ‘As-received' plate and was subjected to 15 pass deformation schedule in plane-strain compression mode inside Gleeble 3500® simulator with true strain of 0.1 per pass starting from 1125°C down to 775°C with an interval of 25°C at the cooling rate of 1°C/s, Fig. 1(a). Blocks of 200mm×125mm×25mm size taken out from the As-received plates were subjected to soaking treatment (1130°C for 1h) followed by hot-rolling at four different deformation temperatures: 1050°C, Fig. 2. The deformation was applied in single rolling pass using ~50% strain (true strain of ~0.7), reducing 25mm As-received plate to 12.5mm thick rolled plates, over a temperature range (~30°C) and the finish rolling temperatures are reported above.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the steel used in this study and the HSLA-100 reported in Ref. [2].
Text: As shown in Table 1 , the investigated steel in this study was prepared with alloy compositions based on those of HSLA-100 steel . The steel was melted in a vacuum melting furnace. The as-cast ingot was austenitized at 1100 °C for 2 h and then hot-rolled into 30-mm-thick plates in 11 passes, followed by slow cooling in a burial pit. The hot-rolled plate was subsequently cut from several locations into blocks 110 mm long (rolling direction), 30 mm wide, and 15 mm thick. These blocks were maintained at 860 °C for 1 h, immediately water quenched, maintained at 760 °C for 1 h, secondarily water quenched, and then finally tempered at 480 °C for 1 h.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the IA and PA specimens.
Text: The forged 100 × 100 mm2 billets were first hot-rolled into 2 mm-thick sheets and then cold rolled to a final thickness of 1 mm. The thickness of the cold-rolled plates was reduced from 2 to 1 mm in seven rolling passes, with a thickness reduction of 10-15% per pass. No inter-deformation annealing was performed. The specimens required for further investigation were wire-cut from the cold-rolled sheets along the rolling direction (RD). Based on the dilatometry measurements, two different annealing heat treatments were conducted, namely IA at 680 °C (within the IA temperature range) for 30 min in a muffle furnace.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the experimental steels.
Text: The materials, 70×78×80mm in size, for hot rolling were cut from the forged slabs. The hot rolling was carried out on a pilot rolling mill with 370mm diameter twin rolls. According to the previous work, the continuous cooling transformation (CCT) diagrams of the experimental steel measured by Formastor-F and Gleeble-3500 , the parameters for TMCP were designed as designated in Fig. 1 and measured as listed in Table 2 . The materials were heated at 1056°C for 50min and hot rolled from 70mm to 7mm thick plates by seven steps. The finish rolling temperature (FRT) was chosen as 854°C. In order to obtain AF microstructure, the cooling rate (CR) was chosen to be about 21°C/s. The simulated coiling temperature (SCT) was 600 °C.

Table_topic: Table III Room-Temperature Tensile Properties of the Steels
Text: An overall grain refinement effect was expected by rolling with a high rolling reduction ratio (over 80 pct) in the nonrecrystallized region of austenite, after austenitization at 1150 °C.[3,4] This high rolling reduction ratio leads to an increase in dislocation density and subsequent grain refinement, because dislocations act as ferrite initiation sites during cooling. The rolling of all of the four steels was finished at the temperature of the austenite single-phase region above Ar3. After the finish rolling, the steels were rapidly cooled from 790 °C to the finish cooling temperatures of 550 °C to ~650 °C at a cooling rate of 10 °C/s to ~15 °C/s. The final plate thickness was 15 mm.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of studied steels.
Text: The as-cast strip was produced by a twin-roll strip caster (vertical type) available at the State Key Laboratory of Rolling and Automation (RAL). The roller width and diameter of cast rollers were 110mm and 500mm, respectively. The liquid steel was poured into a pre-heated tundish (1180°C) and subsequently allowed to flow into cast rollers forming a molten pool. Next, the liquid steel was solidified and deformed by cast rollers (roller gap 2.2mm, casting speed 30m/min). Lastly, the as-cast strip was firstly cooled to 950°C by water and then was cooled to room temperature in air. The thickness of the as-cast strip was ~ 2.2mm. Subsequently, two different processing routes were adopted to process the as-cast strip: (II) To obtain a martensitic structure, the as-cast strip was heat treated at 1050°C for 10min, followed by quenching.  the as-cast strip was directly cold rolled to 0.8mm with 64% reduction and then annealed at 780°C for 3min (heating rate of ~ 15°C/s), followed by water quenching.

Table_topic: Tensile test results of hot rolled-air cooled and cold deformed samples.
Text: A 25kVA air induction furnace was used to manufacture the investigated steel with the chemical composition shown in Table 1. After cropping the top section of the ingot containing shrinkage/pipes, the remaining portion of 200mm×50mm×50mm size was hot forged down to 16mm thick slab. This was further soaked at 1200°C for 40min and subsequently rolled down to 8mm thick plate in three passes at the finish rolling temperature of 800°C. The hot rolled and air cooled samples were solution treated at 1040°C for 1h to remove any inhomogeneities followed by water quenching to room temperature.

Table_topic: Tensile test results of hot rolled-air cooled and cold deformed samples.
Text: A 25kVA air induction furnace was used to manufacture the investigated steel with the chemical composition shown in Table 1. After cropping the top section of the ingot containing shrinkage/pipes, the remaining portion of 200mm×50mm×50mm size was hot forged down to 16mm thick slab. This was further soaked at 1200°C for 40min and subsequently rolled down to 8mm thick plate in three passes at the finish rolling temperature of 800°C. The hot rolled and air cooled samples were solution treated at 1040°C for 1h to remove any inhomogeneities followed by water quenching to room temperature. Subsequently, the above solution treated samples were cold rolled down to 10% reduction in thickness in several passes, using a laboratory scale rolling mill.

Table_topic: Summary of room-temperature tensile properties of all tested specimens.
Text: Raw steels for cold rolling are actually hot-rolled strips. The chemical composition of the studied alloy is provided in Table 1 . Therefore, two different thermo-mechanical processes, as shown in Fig. 1(b), were applied to produce the final products. The alloyed steels were prepared by vacuum melting and cast into ingots with thickness of 40 mm. The ingots were first heated to 1250 °C for 2 h for full austenization and then hot-rolled to 5 mm in thickness through five passes with two different FRTs of about 840 ± 10 °C. On the other hand, the sheets subjected to a FRT of 840 °C were air-cooled to about 400 °C, followed by isothermal holding at 400 °C for 1 h and finally furnace cooling to room temperature as well.

Table_topic: Summary of room-temperature tensile properties of all tested specimens.
Text: Raw steels for cold rolling are actually hot-rolled strips. The chemical composition of the studied alloy is provided in Table 1 . Therefore, two different thermo-mechanical processes, as shown in Fig. 1(b), were applied to produce the final products. The alloyed steels were prepared by vacuum melting and cast into ingots with thickness of 40 mm. The ingots were first heated to 1250 °C for 2 h for full austenization and then hot-rolled to 5 mm in thickness through five passes with two different FRTs of about 890 ± 10 °C . The sheets subjected to a FRT of 890 °C were directly water-quenched to about 400 °C, then isothermally treated at 400 °C for 1 h to simulate the coiling environment, and finally furnace cooled to room temperature.

Table_topic: Table II Mechanical Properties of the Experimental Steels Following the TMCP
Text: The experimental steels were fabricated in a vacuum induction melting furnace. During melting, the furnace chamber was maintained in an Ar atmosphere. The 80 mm × 100 mm × 400 mm ingots were reheated to 1473 K (1200 °C) for 2 hours and rolled into 13-mm-thick plates by thermo-mechanical control processing (TMCP) in both the recrystallized and the non-recrystallized zones in order to obtain a microstructure of ferrite and pearlite. Initially, the ingots were rolled into 45 mm at 1423 K (1150 °C) for 2 passes. After air cooling to 1143 K (870 °C), the plates were rolled into 13 mm for 5 passes, then cooled at 15 to 20 K s-1 to 893 K (620 °C) by water.

Table_topic: Table III Room-Temperature Tensile Properties of the Four Free-Machining Steels
Text: A bloom of 300 × 400 × 6400 mm in size made by continuous casting was homogenized at 1523 K (1250 °C) for 5 h at a furnace and was rolled to make billets of 160 × 160 mm in cross-sectional area. The billets were maintained at 1473 K (1200 °C) for 3 hours and were hot rolled and cold drawn to produce bars of 25 mm in diameter. The fabricated 25-mm-diameter bars were sectioned in parallel to the rolling direction, polished, and etched in a nital solution.

Table_topic: Tensile property of different TWIP steels.
Text: Four Fe-Mn-C steels were cast with 25kg vacuum medium frequency induction melting furnace. The as cast ingots of TWIP steel with 120mm in diameter and 250mm (excluding hot-top) in height were heated to 1200°C and soaked for 2h by box-type muffle furnace, then forged into rectangular bars sized about 30mm × 80mm × 1000mm. The finishing temperature was higher than 900°C, and the hot forged samples were cooled to room temperature by air convection. Hot rolling was carried out on hot forged samples by a double roller machine at 1100°C after soaking at 1200°C for 1h. After five passes, the forged bars were rolled to plates with thickness between 3.9-4.0mm, then the samples with temperatures higher than 900°C were cooled in furnace. Cold rolled was operated after pickling by aqueous hydrochloric acid solution at room temperature. The final sheets were about 1.6mm in thickness after ten passes with the total reduction rate about 60%. Finally, the sheet samples were heat treated at 750°C for 10min, then air-cooled to 25°C.

Table_topic: Tensile property of different TWIP steels.
Text: Four Fe-Mn-C steels were cast with 25kg vacuum medium frequency induction melting furnace. The as cast ingots of TWIP steel with 120mm in diameter and 250mm (excluding hot-top) in height were heated to 1200°C and soaked for 2h by box-type muffle furnace, then forged into rectangular bars sized about 30mm × 80mm × 1000mm. The finishing temperature was higher than 900°C, and the hot forged samples were cooled to room temperature by air convection. Hot rolling was carried out on hot forged samples by a double roller machine at 1100°C after soaking at 1200°C for 1h. After five passes, the forged bars were rolled to plates with thickness between 3.9-4.0mm, then the samples with temperatures higher than 900°C were cooled in furnace. Cold rolled was operated after pickling by aqueous hydrochloric acid solution at room temperature. The final sheets were about 1.6mm in thickness after ten passes with the total reduction rate about 60%. Finally, the sheet samples were heat treated at 750°C for 10min, then air-cooled to 25°C.

Table_topic: Characteristic tensile properties of AISI 4140 steels with different processing states.
Text: The experimental steel investigated in this study is a commercial AISI 4140 steel with the chemical composition provided in Table 1. The 20mm thick slab cutted from extruded and annealed steel rod was austenized at 850°C for 1h followed by air cooling to 700°C in 10s, then the slab was warm rolled using a φ350mm rolling mill and finally subjected to water quenching. During warm rolling, the time spent for different rolling processes were 20s.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical properties of LCT and HCT samples
Text: The industrial heat was produced in a 200 MT Electric Arc Furnace (CONARC) and the final chemistry was adjusted in Laddle Furnace (LF) station. The liquid metal was casted into 1250 mm width and 62 mm thick slab in a CSP caster. The Compact Strip Production process is a combination of the thin slab casting and direct rolling processes. The thin slab (50–70 mm thick) from CSP was first descaled, sheared to the desired length and then transported at 960–970 °C to a RLNG fired soaking furnace set between 1110 and 1150 °C where it was soaked for 15–25 min. The slab was again descaled and hot-rolled using a 6-stand hot rolling mill to 6 mm thick plates. The hot strips exited the mill at temperatures between 800 and 900 °C in the austenitic condition and were then cooled on the run-out table with water spray before being coiled at specific temperature. In the present study, two strips were produced; one at lower coiling temperature of 520 °C (named LCT sample).

Table_topic: Summary of mechanical properties of TWIP steel under various processing conditions.
Text: The steel composition furnished in Table 1 was prepared in a 25 kVA air induction melting furnace. Table_topic: Table 2 Room-temperature tensile properties of the hot-forged and hot-rolled specimens
Text: The medium-Mn, high-Si multicomponent steel was prepared through melting-casting route in a vacuum induction furnace under argon atmosphere. The chemical composition of the alloy is given in Table 1. The ingot of dimensions 150 mm × 30 mm × 30 mm was homogenized at 1373 K for 1 h and then subjected to 50% reduction through hot forging with the finish forging temperature of 1310 K, followed by water quenching. Table_topic: Tensile properties of CR, WR and annealed samples.
Text: The as-received strips were solution annealed at 1050 °C for 30 min followed by quenching to room temperature. After surface descaling by acid pickling, the plates were subjected to cold rolling at room temperature and warm rolling at 200 °C, referred as CR and WR, respectively. The total reduction was ~85%, and the final thickness was ~0.9 mm. The subsequent annealing treatments were carried out in an electric furnace. Samples for TEM observation were cut from the deformed sheets by wire electrode cutting and then mechanically ground to a thickness of 40-50 μm. The as-received strips were solution annealed at 1050 °C for 30 min followed by quenching to room temperature. After surface descaling by acid pickling, the plates were subjected to warm rolling at 200 °C, referred as WR.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of experimental cold rolled steels after final annealing at 950 degC.
Text: The melts were cast into 100 mm × 100 mm square ingots, which were subsequently hot rolled to 2-2.5 mm sheets in three stages. In the first stage, ingots were rolled into 18-20 mm thick plates through five passes after soaking at 1100 °C for 2.5 h. In the second stage, once again these plates were soaked for 1 h at 1100 °C and hot rolled into 4-5 mm thick plates. In the third stage of rolling, 4-5 mm thick plates were hot rolled to 2-2.5 mm thick sheets after soaking at 1100 °C for 10 min. The finishing temperature was in the range of 780-850 °C. However, the studied sheets were selected with finishing temperature at 800 °C. Cold rolling of hot bands of 2.1-2.5 mm thickness was performed after pickling in 40% HCl maintained at 70-85 °C and washed thoroughly in tap water and then dried under sun rays. The pickled sheets were cold rolled into 0.49-0.53 mm thickness after 5-7 passes in experimental cold rolling mill.

Table_topic:
Influence of austenitization temperature (tAUS
=6min) on the former austenitic grain size, yield strength, tensile strength, and elongation to rupture of steel 22MnB5.
Text: Steel sheets of 22MnB5 with a thickness of 1.5mm, manufactured by Thyssen Krupp Steel in Duisburg (Germany) were used as the substrate material. An AlSi10Fe3 layer with a thickness of 17 or 25μm was deposited on the 22MnB5 by hot dipping at a temperature of typically 675°C. The chemical composition of steel 22MnB5 was measured by optical emission spark spectroscopy and is given in Table 1 . Squared specimens (20×20mm) were heat-treated in an argon atmosphere in an inert gas furnace. Three different austenitization temperatures, namely TAUS =920, 950, and 1000°C, and a dwell time of tAUS =1, 2, 4, 6, 10, 20, and 30min were used for each specimen. The heating rate of 7.6°C/s was adapted to the austenitizing parameters (tAUS =6min, TAUS =920°C) which are used for an industrial press hardening process, conventionally. At the end of the dwell time specified for the respective sample, austenitizing was followed by water quenching. Before testing, the tensile specimens were heat-treated at 920°C with a dwell time of 6min, and subsequently quenched in water.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of the experimental steels produced in different cooling processes.
Text: The 150 mm thick slabs were heated to 1200 °C and held for 2 h to dissolve the microalloyed elements. The slabs were rolled into steel plates with 24 mm thickness on the φ450 mm two-high reversing hot rolling mill and cooled using the UFC system. The recrystallization controlled rolling with the initial rolling temperature of ~1120 °C, the finishing temperature of ~1060 °C, and the total reduction ratio of ~63.3% was performed. The non-recrystallization controlled rolling with the initial rolling temperature of ~885 °C, the finishing temperature of ~855 °C, and the total reduction ratio of ~56.4% was performed. After finish rolling, the hot rolled plates were cooled by using cooling process A (CPA) of direct quenching (DQ) to room temperature. After TMCP, the experimental steels of different cooling processes tempered at 680°C for 60 min (denoted by CPA-T, CPB-T and CPC-T).

Text: Modified 9Cr-1Mo steel plate (400mm×250mm×25mm) of composition as given in Table 1 has been received from IGCAR, Kalpakkam in normalized and tempered condition. The hot-rolled material was normalized at 1050°C for 25min, air-cooled and tempered at 750°C for 75min. Therefore, the ‘As-received' material has already been austenitized once after rolling.

Table_topic: Tensile properties obtained from the tension test on the investigated samples.
Text: Modified 9Cr-1Mo steel plate (400mm×250mm×25mm) of composition as given in Table 1 has been received from IGCAR, Kalpakkam in normalized and tempered condition. The hot-rolled material was normalized at 1050°C for 25min, air-cooled and tempered at 750°C for 75min. Therefore, the ‘As-received' material has already been austenitized once after rolling. Blocks of 100mm×250mm×25mm size were cut from the As-received plate and were reheated at a heating rate of 10°C/min to three different austenitization temperatures: 950°C (950-Reheat). The blocks were soaked for 1h, air-cooled to room temperature and finally tempered again at 750°C for 1h. The heat-treatment schedule employed in the present study is summarized in the schematic diagram in Fig. 1.

Table_topic: Average tensile test values of specimens.
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum melting furnace and forged into billets of section dimensions of 60 mm × 60 mm. The billets were homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h and hot rolled to 4 mm via seven passes with the finish rolling temperature of ~890 °C, and subsequently air cooled to 690 °C followed by cooling in furnace to simulate coiling. After acid pickling with 20% HCl aqueous solution, the hot rolled slab was cold rolled to a thickness of ~1 mm for preparing tensile specimens and cold rolled to a thickness of ~1.5 mm for preparing dilatometric specimens. The specimens were annealed in a tubular resistance furnace at 800 °C for 360 s, then quickly placed in a salt bath furnace at 400 °C for 500 s, and finally quenched to room temperature. In order to study the austenite transformation behavior during the annealing stage, interrupted annealing tests were performed, i.e. heating to 760 °C, 780 °C and 800 °C, followed by rapid quenching to room temperature and annealing at 800 °C for 20s, followed by quenching to room temperature, respectively.

Table_topic: Average tensile test values of specimens.
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum melting furnace and forged into billets of section dimensions of 60 mm × 60 mm. The billets were homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h and hot rolled to 4 mm via seven passes with the finish rolling temperature of ~890 °C, and subsequently air cooled to 690 °C followed by cooling in furnace to simulate coiling. After acid pickling with 20% HCl aqueous solution, the hot rolled slab was cold rolled to a thickness of ~1 mm for preparing tensile specimens and cold rolled to a thickness of ~1.5 mm for preparing dilatometric specimens. The cold-rolled specimens were first annealed at 760 °C for 180 s, and then quenched to ambient temperature to obtain initial microstructure comprising ferrite and martensite structures. The specimens were annealed in a tubular resistance furnace at 800 °C for 360 s, then quickly placed in a salt bath furnace at 400 °C for 500 s, and finally quenched to room temperature. In order to study the austenite transformation behavior during the annealing stage, interrupted annealing tests were performed, i.e. heating to 760 °C, 780 °C and 800 °C, followed by rapid quenching to room temperature and annealing at 800 °C for 20s, followed by quenching to room temperature, respectively.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical property of experimental steel for varied cooling processes
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace with a capacity of 150 kg and cast into ingots. The chemical composition of the steel is given in Table 1. Ingots of experimental steel were forged into plates of 100 mm × 100 mm × 120 mm size, from which dilatometry specimens of dimensions 6 mm in diameter and 12 mm in length were machined for measurement of Ac1 and Ac3 using Gleeble-3800 thermo-mechanical simulator, and the results were 697 and 807 °C, respectively. Ingots of thickness ~100 mm were reheated at 1250 °C for 2 h for solution treatment and then hot rolled via 2 passes to a final thickness of ~12 mm. After hot rolling, two types of cooling processes were adopted during the phase transformation of austenite to bainite to control the precipitates and mechanical properties: (I) ultrafast cooling to ~630 °C and then air cooling to room temperature, the cooling rate of the ultrafast cooling was ~80 °C/s.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical property of experimental steel for varied cooling processes
Text: The steel was melted in a vacuum induction furnace with a capacity of 150 kg and cast into ingots. The chemical composition of the steel is given in Table 1. Ingots of experimental steel were forged into plates of 100 mm × 100 mm × 120 mm size, from which dilatometry specimens of dimensions 6 mm in diameter and 12 mm in length were machined for measurement of Ac1 and Ac3 using Gleeble-3800 thermo-mechanical simulator, and the results were 697 and 807 °C, respectively. Ingots of thickness ~100 mm were reheated at 1250 °C for 2 h for solution treatment and then hot rolled via 2 passes to a final thickness of ~12 mm. After hot rolling, two types of cooling processes were adopted during the phase transformation of austenite to bainite to control the precipitates and mechanical properties: (II) accelerated cooling to ~630 °C and then air cooling to room temperature, the cooling rate of the accelerated cooling was ~15 °C/s.

Table_topic: Tensile test results for the four steels after rolling stage.
Text: To investigate the effect of Cu and Ni elements on increasing the strength/toughness of high Ni HSLA steels, four chemical compositions with different weight percent of Cu and Ni (Ni to Cu ratio of about 2) were selected based on chemical composition of HSLA-100 (standard MIL-S-24645). Samples were numbered from A1 to A4 based on the gradual increment of Cu and Ni content. The four chemical compositions were melted in a 10 kg inductoterm induction furnace with the frequency of 75 kw. The ingots were then uniformed and pre-heated in an electric furnace held at 1200 °C with the precision of ± 10 °C. The ingots were hot rolled with a two stand rolling mill instrument with the rolls diameter of 400 mm and rolls width of 700 mm. The rolling process was applied in two stages: roughing stage with overall area reduction of 68% in both longitudinal and transfer directions; and finishing stage rolling with overall reduction of 47% in the longitudinal direction.

Samples were numbered from A1 to A4 based on the gradual increment of Cu and Ni content. The four chemical compositions were melted in a 10 kg inductoterm induction furnace with the frequency of 75 kw. The ingots were then uniformed and pre-heated in an electric furnace held at 1200 °C with the precision of ± 10 °C. The ingots were hot rolled with a two stand rolling mill instrument with the rolls diameter of 400 mm and rolls width of 700 mm. The rolling process was applied in two stages: roughing stage with overall area reduction of 68% in both longitudinal and transfer directions; and finishing stage rolling with overall reduction of 47% in the longitudinal direction. One set of samples (A11, A21, A31, A41) were austenitized at 920 °C for 45 min in an induction furnace and directly quenched afterward.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the hot rolled super FSSs No. 1 and No. 2
Text: Two super FSS grades (26Cr-3.5Mo-2Ni and 29Cr-3.5Mo-2Ni, denoted hereafter by No. 1 and No. 2, respectively) were first melted in a 150-kg vacuum induction furnace. The casting ingots with a diameter of 120 mm were then hot forged to slabs of 35 mm × 300 mm × 600 mm in dimension at temperature of 1200 to 1000 °C, and the slabs were subsequently hot rolled to 6 mm plates at 1150-900 °C. Finally, these slabs were annealed for 10 min at temperature ranging from 980 to 1100 °C and after that, they were air-cooled.

Table_topic: Tensile test results of the different degradation state of SA508-IV steel.
Text: The chemical composition of the SA508-IV Ni-Cr-Mo low-alloy steel is listed in Table 1 . As shown in Fig. 1 , the specimens were subjected to a heat treatment of 1.5h at 920°C, followed by water quenching (WQ) to room temperature (RT), re-heating to 650°C for 30h and furnace cooling to RT. Specimens without the further TMEP treatment are termed as "the as-received state". The degradation procedure has been worked out with aging, followed by the 10% uniform cold strain (Fig. 1). After standard grinding and polishing, the samples were etched by 5 volume percent (vol.%) nital. The bulk content of Cu in this experimental steel is 0.041wt.%.

The alloys were prepared using vacuum induction melting into 5.7kg ingots. The ingots were forged and rolled at 1100°C into 15mm thick slabs. The slabs were then heated to 1250°C and held for 30min to dissolve any precipitates and then rolled to 75% reduction at 900°C. After rolling the specimens were first air cooled to 650°C and held for 5min, followed by air cooling to 500°C where it was held for 60min and then furnace cooled to room temperature.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of samples annealed at different temperatures.
Text: 304 austenitic stainless steel of chemical composition listed in Table 1 was studied. The steel sheet of dimensions 50 mm × 60 mm × 120 mm was homogenized at 1200 °C for 3 h before hot rolling via 7 passes using Φ450 mm trial rolling mill and thickness was reduced from 50 to 4.5 mm. The start and finish rolling temperatures were 1180 °C and 1080 °C, respectively. The hot-rolled sheet was water-quenched to ambient temperature. The three-stage cold rolling and annealing treatments to obtain nano/ultrafine grains is schematically presented in Fig. 1. Multistage unidirectional cold rolling with uniform reduction in thickness was carried out at room temperature using a four-calendar rolling mill with oil lubrication, and the final thickness of 0.7 mm and total reduction of ~ 85%. Annealing treatments were performed in an electric furnace.

Table_topic: Austenite content and mechanical properties of the material aged to different conditions
Text: The maraging steel used in this study was of 350 Grade vacuum induction melted quality forging of 70mm diameter, in double solution-treated (950°C-2h air-cooled, followed by 820°C-2h air-cooled) condition. Cylindrical tensile specimens of 4mm diameter and 20mm gage length and standard Charpy V-notch impact specimens of 10mm×10mm×55mm were machined along the half-radius location of the rod, with their long axis coinciding with the length of the rod. Ageing of the tensile and impact specimens was carried out in a Kanthal air furnace with a temperature accuracy of ±5°C. Ageing was terminated by quenching the specimens in water maintained at 27°C. After 1 h of ageing at 640 °C the sample possessed an excellent toughness.

Text: The nominal chemical compositions and mechanical properties are given in Tables 1 and 2 , respectively. The standard steps of heat treatment condition RH520 are expressed as follows: solution treatment (1050°C×30min, air-cooled)→cold treatment (-78°C×4h)→aging treatment (520°C×2h, air-cooled). The specimens are ground with sand paper and mechanically polish to 0.5μm, then electrolytic polishing for relief of casehardening. The RH status for the steel is the standard heat treatment and it is suitable for manufacturing components by rods, plates and so on.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the experimental steel.
Text: It was made in a vacuum induction furnace and cast as ingots. The ingot was hot forged into block of thickness ~50 mm. After austenitization at 1200 °C for 2 h, the block was hot rolled to plate of thickness ~6 mm via 7 passes and the finish rolling temperature was higher than 900 °C, followed by air cooling to room temperature. Dilatometry experiments were carried out to study the Ms temperature using cylindrical specimens of dimensions φ 3 × 10 mm2 machined from the hot rolled plate with length direction perpendicular to the rolling direction. The plates were heated to 1100 °C, and held for  1 h. They were subsequently austempered at 300 °C for 1 h to ensure low temperature bainitic transformation, followed by air cooling to room temperature.

Table_topic: Summary of tensile properties of ASR and TMP 13/4 MSS.
Text: The chemical composition analyzed using Thermo Jarrell Ash spark emission spectroscope is shown in Table 1. Ltd., India provided the ingot of this material. The specimens were 0.76mm thick, 1.62mm wide and 4mm long ( Fig. 2).

Table_topic: Measured mechanical properties of steels.
Text: Table 1 lists the chemical compositions of the steels as prepared by laboratory vacuum-induction melting. The specimens were square as-cast slabs of 60mm thickness, 170mm width, and 200mm length. After 1200°C furnace homogenization, the specimens were subjected to a hot-rolling. Specially, the slabs were fed into a rolling mill and passed through seven times, producing 3.2mm-thick hot sheets. The rolling temperature at finishing was about 900°C. After rolling, the hot bands were cooled by a water cooling system. In an investigation of the coiling temperature effect, the coiling temperature of steels A and B was increased from 500 to 600°C. The hot-rolled sheets were then cold-rolled into 0.7mm thicknesses, after which they were annealed at 800°C in an infrared furnace.

Table_topic: Tensile properties of alloys produced by different heat treatments.
Text: A medium-Mn steel (Table 1 ) ingot with dimension of 150 mm*100 mm*250 mm was manufactured by vacuum induction melting. The ingot was austenitized at 1200 °C for 1 h and then hot-rolled to 4-mm thickness. The hot-rolled plate was annealed at 650 °C for 1 h, then cold-rolled to 2-mm thickness with a total reduction ratio of 50%. After cold rolling, the microstructure was deformed martensite, which was heat treated in two ways to achieve different grain morphology (Fig. 1 ). To obtain diverse fractions and mechanical stability of the austenite, the steel was intercritically annealed at 650 °C, and quenched in water.

Table_topic: Table II Yield Strength (YS), Tensile Strength (TS), Elongation (pct), and Area Reduction (pct) Values for Steels 3NbMo0, 3NbMo31, 6NbMo0, and 6NbMo31 and the Coiling Temperatures of 923 K, 823 K, and 723 K (650 °C, 550 °C, and 450 °C)
Text: The specimens were subjected to the thermomechanical schedule depicted in Figure 1. The schedule included reheating at 1523 K (1250 °C) for 5 minutes followed by quenching, in order to insure the dissolution of the Nb precipitates. Then, a soaking treatment was performed at 1323 K (1050 °C) for 5 minutes to promote a fine and homogeneous austenite structure. Afterward, the specimens were deformed in the plane compression machine in the non-recrystallization temperature region, applying a strain of 0.4 at 1 s-1. After a 5 second holding, the samples were cooled down at a constant rate of 10 K/s to three different coiling temperatures of 723 K (450 °C). Coiling was simulated by holding the samples for 1 hour followed by slow cooling in the furnace to room temperature at 1 K/s.

Table_topic: Table 2 Mechanical properties, volume fractions, and carbon contents of the retained austenite of investigated steels
Text: In this study, the experimental steels were vacuum-melted and cast into ingots with weight of 40 kg. The cast ingot was then forged into a block with a thickness of 30 mm. The block was soaked at 1473 K (1200 °C) for 2 h, and hot rolled into a strip with a thickness of 4.5 mm after six passes with a finishing temperature above 1133 K (860 °C). Cold rolling was then followed to further reduce the thickness of the strip to 1.2 mm. A two-stage heat treatment was adopted to obtain the final desired microstructure. In view of the M s and M f temperature of the two experimental steels, samples were rapidly quenched in a salt bath at 593 K (320 °C) after soaking at these IA temperatures for 80 s, held for 3 min, and then air cooled to room temperature (Fig. 2).

Table_topic: Chemical composition (in wt%) and mechanical properties of the MS-AHSS.
Text: The four martensitic AHSS were commercially produced, in the form of rolled-sheet. The four steel grades were given the following designations: MS980, MS1180, MS1300, and MS1500. The mean sheet thicknesses were 1.2mm for MS1300 and MS1500, 1.5mm for MS980, and 1.8mm for MS1180. Table 1 presents the chemical and mechanical properties of the steels, as provided by the steel producer. The specimen thickness corresponded to the steel sheet thickness. These specimens were machined from the steel sheet, and polished with 1200 grit SiC paper.

Table_topic: Room temperature tensile properties of experimental steels.
Text: The steels were melted by means of a 100 kg high-frequency vacuum induction furnace and cast into ingots, following the forging process into a 90 × 200 × 120 mm3 billet between 950 and 1100 °C. After homogenized at 1100 °C for 30 min, the steels were rolled into 18 mm thickness by three passes rough rolling and three passes finish rolling. The finish rolling temperature was about 840 °C with a total reduction of 80%. Subsequently, the steels were quenched to room temperature by laminar water cooling. The quenched steels were reheated to 820 °C for 30 min with water quenching (RQ process) and the equiaxed prior austenite grain was obtained. The heating rate was 200 °C/h, cooling rate was 16 °C/s, and the specimens were preserved at 850 °C for 15 min. The austenite starting transformation temperatures were 564 and 573 °C for 7Mn-0Nb and 7Mn-0.05Nb steels, respectively.

Table_topic: Table 3 Tensile properties of one-step and two-step sample
Text: The ingot was then forged into billets with a transverse dimension of 100 mm × 100 mm. After homogenization at 1200 °C for 2 h, the billet was hot-rolled to 4 mm thickness via nine passes. Subsequently, the hot-rolled plate was air-cooled to room temperature. The hot-rolled plates were then annealed in an annealing furnace, and two different heat treatment routes were designed. As presented in Fig. 1, the conventional heat treatment with an initial fully martensitic structure was intercritical annealed at 640 °C for 2 h and then air-cooled to room temperature (one-step). The dilatometer specimens were prepared from the hot-rolled plate and heated to experimental temperatures at a heating rate of 10 °C/s, then isothermally annealed, followed by cooling to room temperature with a cooling rate of 20 °C/s.

Table_topic: Table 3 Tensile properties of one-step and two-step sample
Text: The ingot was then forged into billets with a transverse dimension of 100 mm × 100 mm. After homogenization at 1200 °C for 2 h, the billet was hot-rolled to 4 mm thickness via nine passes. Subsequently, the hot-rolled plate was air-cooled to room temperature. The hot-rolled plates were then annealed in an annealing furnace, and two different heat treatment routes were designed. The two-step annealing process consisted of pre-annealing at 750 °C for 0.5 h followed by water quenching to room temperature (IA-750), then intercritical annealed at 640 °C for 2 h and finally air-cooled to room temperature (two-step). The dilatometer specimens were prepared from the hot-rolled plate and heated to experimental temperatures at a heating rate of 10 °C/s, then isothermally annealed, followed by cooling to room temperature with a cooling rate of 20 °C/s.

Table_topic: Microstructures and mechanical properties of the two plates.
Text: The SUF steels are water-cooled prior to the completion of the rolling process (i.e., during middle of the rolling process). Thus, reversal austenization can be introduced during the hot rolling process to obtain fine-grained steel plates that involve water-cooling during the middle of the rolling process to transform the plate microstructure, followed by reheating to realize inverse transformation. The chemical composition and key parameters of the experimental steel are listed in Table 1. Steel of initial thickness of 140mm was hot rolled to 15mm using a two-hi 450mm hot rolling mill. Two plates of dimensions 15mm×55mm×300mm were cut from the plate and soaked at 1200°C for 2h, hot rolled to 12mm at 1100°C to refine the austenite grains, and then water-cooled to ~400°C at a cooling rate of ~60°C/s followed by hold time of 60s. After warm deforming, the steel was reheated to 880°C and air-cooled to room temperature at a cooling rate of ~1.3°C/s to obtain ferrite plus pearlite microstructure, and this steel is referred as B3 plate.

Table_topic: Table 3 Mechanical properties of the steels in the quenched and tempered condition
Text: After annealing at 1250 °C for 5 h, ingots were deformed into rods with a diameter of about 35 mm in the temperature range 900-1100 °C using loose tooling forging. The steels were normalized at 880 °C for 30 min, leading to average austenite grain sizes of about 12 μm for LS steel, 14 μm for MS steel, and 15 μm for HS steel. Therefore, the tested steels were end-quenched as per ASTM A 255-10 (Ref 16). The end-quench test specimen (diameter 25 mm; length 102 mm) was heated to 880 °C and held for 30 min. A specimen with dimensions of 3 mm × 3 mm × 3 mm was heated to 880 °C and maintained at this temperature for 30 min. The steels were austenitized at 880 °C for 30 min and then water-quenched and tempered at 430 °C for 60 min. Cylindrical tensile specimens (10 mm in diameter and 100 mm in gauge-length section) were machined from the tempered steels.

Table_topic: Macroscopic parameters characterized during synchrotron experiment for the mechanical response of sample TMP-770 and TMP-790 to the applied tensile stress.
Text: TRIP steel with composition listed in Table 1 was used in this study. Plate-shaped ingots were subjected to laboratory simulations of thermo-mechanical processing (TMP) using a laboratory rolling mill at Deakin University. After reheating to 1250°C and holding for 1800s in a 15kW muffle furnace, the plates were rolled immediately to 25% reduction at 1100°C, held for 120s to condition the austenite microstructure, then cooled at 2K/s to 875°C, where the second deformation of 47% reduction was applied. In order to form various volume fractions of polygonal ferrite (PF), slow cooling at 1K/s after the second deformation through the ferrite formation region was interrupted at 770°C by water mist cooling at 20K/s to 500°C. Following this, the plates were placed into a fluidized bed furnace and covered with aluminum oxide sand for a hold at 470°C for 1200s. After this step, the plates were water quenched.

Table_topic: Table III Mechanical Properties of Steels With and Without Al Alloying
Text: The experimental steel with 0.5 wt pct Al was melted in vacuum induction furnace and 10 kg ingot was casted with a diameter of 100 mm. For comparison, another steel with a similar composition but without Al alloying was also prepared. The chemical compositions of the steels with and without Al alloying were shown in Table I. The ingots were heated to 1473 K (1200 °C) for 2 hours. After air-cooling to 1273 K (1000 °C), the ingots were forged and rolled to plates with section area of 50 × 20 mm2. And the bars were directly quenched to room temperature after rolling at ending temperature of 1193 K (920 °C) and were tempered at 473 K (200 °C) for 2 hours. The dog-bone-shaped tensile specimens with a gauge length of 65 mm, width of 12.5 mm and thickness of 10 mm were machined from the bars in parallel to the rolling (RD) direction. The microstructure, mechanical properties and impact fracture behaviors of two low-alloy high-strength martensitic steels with and without Al alloying were investigated.

Table_topic: The tensile properties of stainless steel clad plates with different rolling reduction ratios.
Text: Carbon steel plates with dimension of 200 × 240 × 60 mm and 304 stainless steel plates with dimension of 160 × 200 × 12 mm were prepared for hot-rolling preparation. The rolling process was carried out after soaking the built-up slab at 1200 °C for 120min. The thicknesses of the five clad plates were reduced after three passes, and total rolling reduction ratios are 40%. Finally, the hot products were naturally cooled in air and afterwards cut for testing. Samples were cut from the rolled stainless steel clad plates and prepared using conventional metallographic technologies.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of a micro-alloy steel of various states tested in air at a nominal strain rate.
Text: A micro-alloy (MA) steel was obtained in plate form of thickness 6.0mm from Tata Steel, Jamshedpur, India. The chemical composition (wt%) of the alloy is given in Table 1. The alloy plates are hot rolled and the hot rolling parameters of the micro-alloy steel were: soaking temperature 1185°C, finish rolling temperature 910°C and coiling temperature 580°C. In order to produce different grain sizes of the steel, the as-received plate was subjected to various annealing and rapid cooling heat treatments, given in Table 2. For TEM study, the samples of the as-received and a heat treated steel coupons were mechanically thinned down to approximately 80μm thickness, then disc of 3mm diameter were punched out. Standard tensile specimens were prepared from the as-received and heat treated alloy and tensile testing was carried out using a servohydrolic universal testing machine (UTM 60) of 600kN capacity at a cross-head speed of 2.0mm/min.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of hot-rolled specimens.
Text: The two steels are Nb micro-alloyed and V-Ti micro-alloyed, which are termed hereafter as Nb steel and V-Ti steel, respectively. According to the designed chemical composition, the steel ingots were smelted in a vacuum smelting furnace under an Ar atmosphere. The contents of hydrogen and oxygen in steels were controlled below 2.5 ppm and 15 ppm by vacuum melting respectively, which were measured by Leco Oxygen Nitrogen Hydrogen Analyzer (TCH 600), as show in Fig. 1 of Supplementary Materials. The as-prepared castings were then heated at 1150 °C for 2 h and hot forged to billets with a cross-section dimension of 45 × 70 mm2. Then, after homogenized at 1200 °C for 2 h, the slabs were hot rolled to 3.0 mm in thickness through five passes within the temperatures range of 1050-850 °C, followed by laminar cooling to 400 °C (cooling rate, 30-50 °C.s-1) and air cooling to ambient temperature to avoid the formation of pearlite.

Table_topic: Room temperature tensile properties of the experimental steels.
Text: The commercial PF pipeline steel was reheated at 1180°C for 230min, and then rolled in two stages, rough-rolling and finish-rolling. The rough-rolling stage for the steel was started for rolling at 1130°C from thickness of 230-40mm in seven steps; then the finish-rolling stage was started at 1020°C and finished rolling at 840°C from thickness of 40-7mm in another seven steps, and after that the steel was cooled to 600°C at 20°C/s for coiling and finally air cooled to room temperature. The laboratory developed AF pipeline steel, designed by the authors, was smelted in a 100-kg vacuum induction furnace. According to our previous work, the continuous cooling transformation (CCT) diagrams of the experimental steel measured by Formastor-F and Gleeble-3500 , the hot rolling experiment was carried out on a pilot rolling mill with twin rolls of 370mm in diameter. The AF pipeline steel was reheated at 1150°C for 50min, started rolling at 1050°C and finished rolling at 750°C from thickness of 70-7mm in seven steps, then cooled to 600°C at 20°C/s in order to obtain the AF microstructure, finally held at 600°C for 1h and furnace cooled to room temperature to simulate the coiling process. Specimens taken from the transverse cross-section planes of the steels were mechanically polished and etched by a 3pct nital solution, and then microstructures were observed by an S-3400N scanning electron microscope (SEM). Specimens for tensile tests were cut from the middle of the rolled plates in the longitudinal direction and tests were conducted at room temperature at a crosshead speed of 5mm/min on a SCHENCK-100KN servo-hydraulic machine, according to the standard of ASTM E8M-04. Thin foils for TEM observation were taken from the transverse cross-section planes of the steel plates, mechanically thinned from 300 to 50μm, electropolished by a twin-jet electropolisher in an electrolyte consisting of 10vol pct perchloric acid and 90vol pct ethanol, and then were examined on a JEM-2010 high resolution TEM operating at 200kV.

Table_topic: Room temperature tensile properties of the experimental steels.
Text: The commercial PF pipeline steel was reheated at 1180°C for 230min, and then rolled in two stages, rough-rolling and finish-rolling. The rough-rolling stage for the steel was started for rolling at 1130°C from thickness of 230-40mm in seven steps; then the finish-rolling stage was started at 1020°C and finished rolling at 840°C from thickness of 40-7mm in another seven steps, and after that the steel was cooled to 600°C at 20°C/s for coiling and finally air cooled to room temperature. The laboratory developed AF pipeline steel, designed by the authors, was smelted in a 100-kg vacuum induction furnace. According to our previous work, the continuous cooling transformation (CCT) diagrams of the experimental steel measured by Formastor-F and Gleeble-3500 , the hot rolling experiment was carried out on a pilot rolling mill with twin rolls of 370mm in diameter. The AF pipeline steel was reheated at 1150°C for 50min, started rolling at 1050°C and finished rolling at 750°C from thickness of 70-7mm in seven steps, then cooled to 600°C at 20°C/s in order to obtain the AF microstructure, finally held at 600°C for 1h and furnace cooled to room temperature to simulate the coiling process. Table_topic: Tensile properties of annealed experimental steels.
Text: The experimental steels were melted in a vacuum induction furnace and cast as 155 kg ingots. The chemical composition of the experimental steels in weight percent is shown in Table 1 . Low carbon of ~0.065% and medium Mn of ~5.5% alloying was designed. To study the effect of Ti content on the microstructural evolution and mechanical properties of low C medium Mn steel, Ti content was selected as 0.014% (steel A), 0.032% (steel B), and 0.053% (steel C), respectively. A schematic illustration of TMCP and annealing process of experimental steels is shown in Fig. 1 . The slabs with thickness of 140 mm were heated to 1200 °C and holding for 3 h in a heating furnace, and then air-cooled to 1000 °C.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the experimental steels.
Text: A Ti-Nb-Mo and Ti-Nb microalloyed steels (referred as A and B) were melted in a high frequency induction furnace and cast as 40kg ingots. The ingots were forged into 80mm thick square billet after soaking at 1200°C for 2h and thermomechanically processed using a laboratory-scale rolling mill. The billet was subjected to ~85% reduction to final thickness of 12mm. The end temperature of the finish rolling was controlled to 835°C, thereafter, the 12mm thick plates was air cooled at a cooling rate of ~2°C/s to 600°C and then water-quenched to room temperature, as schematically shown in Fig. 1. Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) foils were prepared by cutting slices from the plates, mechanically thinning to 0.05mm, and twin-jet electropolishing to perforation using a solution of 5% perchloric acid and 95% ethanol at -20°C.

Table_topic: Vickers hardness test, tensile test, and Charpy impact test results of the high-P-containing steels.
Text: Four high-P-containing steels were made by a vacuum induction melting method, and their chemical compositions were shown in Table 1. The contents of P and B were controlled to be 200 or 500ppm and 0 or 20ppm, respectively. For convenience, the steels containing 200ppm and 500ppm of P are referred to as '2P' and '5P', respectively, and the steels additionally containing 20ppm of B in the 2P and 5P steels are referred to as ‘2PB' and ‘5PB', respectively. The rolling and heat-treatment conditions are shown in Fig. 1. After the austenitization at 1200°C for 2h, the rolling was started at 900°C and finished at 880°C. The plate thickness was reduced from 30mm to 7mm during rolling. The rolled plates were air-cooled down to the coiling temperature of 620°C, held at this temperature for 1h, and air-cooled to room temperature. The isothermal heat-treatments were then conducted to produce similar ferrite-pearlite-based microstructures, irrespective of steels. The steel plates were austenitized at 900°C for 30min, held at 550°C for 3h in a salt-bath to produce ferrite-pearlite- or ferrite-bainite-based microstructures, respectively, and air-cooled to room temperature.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the experimental steels.
Text: The 0Cr16Ni5Mo and 40CrNiMoA steels were both supplied in the form of a rod with a diameter of 45mm, which were prepared by vacuum induction melting and electroslag remelting. The 40CrNiMoA steel was austenitized at 860°C for 2.5h, oil cooled, tempered at 540°C, and air cooled. The pre-charged specimens used for hydrogen charging were prepared with a diameter of 5mm and a length of 40mm, which were supplied by as-received heat-treated bars. Both TDS analysis and SSRT specimens were treated as the same condition that ground with SiC papers and cleaned ultrasonically in anhydrous alcohol.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of the experimental steels.
Text: The 0Cr16Ni5Mo and 40CrNiMoA steels were both supplied in the form of a rod with a diameter of 45mm, which were prepared by vacuum induction melting and electroslag remelting. The 0Cr16Ni5Mo steel was first austenitized at 960°C for 2.5h, water cooled, and tempered at 520°C for 4h, and air cooled. The pre-charged specimens used for hydrogen charging were prepared with a diameter of 5mm and a length of 40mm, which were supplied by as-received heat-treated bars. Both TDS analysis and SSRT specimens were treated as the same condition that ground with SiC papers and cleaned ultrasonically in anhydrous alcohol.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of as rolled and tempered steels.
Text: Low carbon steel was designed and prepared in a 25kg vacuum induction furnace. After the casting in the vacuum atmosphere the ingot was directly cooled into water, and then the steel was forged into an 80mm thick slab. The chemical composition of the steel is listed in Table 1 . The measured Ac1 and Ac3 temperatures for the present steel were 712 and 810°C respectively. After forging, the steel was reheated to 1200°C and held for 2h, and then it was rolled to 10mm thick plate. The plates were then cooled in air to 800°C from the finish rolling temperature (relaxation process) and followed by the accelerated cooling to 400°C, and then cooled to room temperature in air.

Table_topic: Mechanical properties of as rolled and tempered steels.
Text: Low carbon steel was designed and prepared in a 25kg vacuum induction furnace. After the casting in the vacuum atmosphere the ingot was directly cooled into water, and then the steel was forged into an 80mm thick slab. The chemical composition of the steel is listed in Table 1 . The measured Ac1 and Ac3 temperatures for the present steel were 712 and 810°C respectively. After forging, the steel was reheated to 1200°C and held for 2h, and then it was rolled to 10mm thick plate. The plates were then cooled in air to 800°C from the finish rolling temperature (relaxation process) and followed by the accelerated cooling to 400°C, and then cooled to room temperature in air. In order to investigate the effect of tempering on the properties the samples were tempered at 600°C for 0.5 and 1h.
